{"type":"custom_message","customType":"openclaw.runtime-context","content":"[media attached: media://inbound/758e7df6-872d-46c8-967a-e3713bdab6f3.jpg (image/jpeg) | media://inbound/758e7df6-872d-46c8-967a-e3713bdab6f3.jpg]\nTo send an image back, prefer the message tool (media/path/filePath). If you must inline, use MEDIA:https://example.com/image.jpg (spaces ok, quote if needed) or a safe relative path like MEDIA:./image.jpg. Absolute and ~ paths only work when they stay inside your allowed file-read boundary; host file:// URLs are blocked. Keep caption in the text body.\nSystem: [2026-05-23 20:04:00 GMT+8] Feishu[default] DM | ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb [msg:om_x100b6e2d3413d4a8c25c87d6eb07628, image, 1 attachment(s)]\n\n[Image]\nUser text:\n[Feishu ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb Sat 2026-05-23 20:04 GMT+8] ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb: /home/halei/.openclaw/media/inbound/758e7df6-872d-46c8-967a-e3713bdab6f3.jpg\nDescription:\nThe image shows a dark-themed dashboard interface. The left sidebar lists items like \"tts / main\" (highlighted), \"finance / main,\" and \"review / main.\" The main panel displays successful log entries for \"gateway\" and \"tool.\" A status message identifies a bound Feishu/Lark Bot named \"TK 选品大师\" with App ID `cli_a930f78f51399bc6`. It further specifies a message whitelist policy (`dmPolicy: allowlist`) restricted to a specific user ID starting with `ou_f590c429...`.","display":false,"details":{"source":"openclaw-runtime-context"},"id":"203173a7","parentId":"b197e177","timestamp":"2026-05-23T12:04:31.829Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"08e56442","parentId":"203173a7","timestamp":"2026-05-23T12:05:24.936Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is showing me screenshots of the OpenClaw web UI. The image shows:\n\n1. Left sidebar shows \"tts / main\" (highlighted), \"finance / main\", \"review / main\"\n2. The main panel shows successful log entries for \"gateway\" and \"tool\"\n3. A status message identifies a bound Feishu/Lark Bot named \"TK 选品大师\" with App ID `cli_a930f78f51399bc6`\n4. It specifies a message whitelist policy (`dmPolicy: allowlist`) restricted to a specific user ID starting with `ou_f590c429...`\n\nSo from the web UI, the tts account is properly configured with the allowlist policy and the user's open_id is in the whitelist.\n\nThe user confirmed:\n1. They're messaging the correct TK bot in Feishu\n2. The message goes through with no reply\n3. The web UI shows the tts account is active and properly configured\n4. All other agents work fine\n5. Only TK选品大师 doesn't reply from Feishu\n\nThis is a very specific routing issue. Since the web UI works for tts (meaning the bot CAN receive and process messages in the web UI), but Feishu messages don't get replied to, the issue is likely in how Feishu routes messages to the tts bot.\n\nWait - actually, let me reconsider. The user says \"选品大师子在openclaw自身的webui后台 是可以回复的\". This means when they use the OpenClaw web UI (not Feishu), they can chat with the TK选品大师 agent and get replies. So the agent itself is working fine.\n\nThe problem is specifically that when they send a message in Feishu to the TK bot, there's no reply.\n\nThis means the Feishu message is reaching OpenClaw (because the user sees it going to the right account in the web UI status), but the tts agent isn't responding to it.\n\nOne possibility: the tts agent is using a different workspace (`workspace-tts`) and might have issues with its session or message handling. Let me check if there are recent sessions in the tts workspace that show messages being received but not responded to.\n \nLooking at the recent tts session file (e93a01b9-8c85-4f1d-89f5-5a4af2771503.jsonl), I can see it's from May 23 at 09:00-09:02 and shows a cron job triggered the agent to run product selection, then at 09:01 it was reading docs/SOP.md and calling the Sorftime MCP before hitting an overload error. But there's no record of any direct Feishu messages to the tts agent in that session.\n\nThe fact that a cron job session exists but no user messages appear suggests the tts account might be routing Feishu messages to kiit instead. When the user sends a message to the TK bot in Feishu, they're getting a response from kiit rather than tts, which would explain why the user thinks it's not working—they're actually receiving replies, just from the wrong agent. I need to check if the tts account is properly configured or if there's a routing issue causing messages to go to kiit instead.\n\nLooking at the session data more carefully, the most recent tts session is from 09:00 on May 23, and the user hasn't reported new activity since our fix at around 10:00. But they said \"still doesn't work,\" which means they likely tested sending a new message to the TK bot after our configuration change. If that message was received by tts, it should have created a new session file, but I only see the old cron job session. This suggests either the message never reached tts, or it's being handled differently than expected.\n\nThe tkinter bot might be receiving messages but unable to respond if its Telegram bot token is invalid or missing. However, the user mentioned they're testing via Feishu, not Telegram, so I need to focus on why Feishu messages aren't generating responses from the tkinter agent. The fact that the web UI can successfully send messages to tts proves the bot is functional, so the issue likely lies in how incoming Feishu messages are being processed or routed to the tkinter agent.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a session management problem—the bot might only maintain one active session at a time, and the cron job could be holding it open, preventing new messages from creating fresh sessions. Looking at the workspace configuration, the tts agent uses `workspace-tts` as its workspace directory, which is properly set in the config. But there might be a `sessionScope` setting that's interfering with how the bot handles concurrent or queued sessions.\n\nActually, the most likely culprit is simpler—when you press the \"chat\" button for the tts bot in the web UI, it spawns a session and communicates via a specific channel (like `feishu:tts`). But when a Feishu message arrives from the user, it goes through the tts account and creates a different session key format. The incoming Feishu message might be creating a session that doesn't properly get routed back to the Feishu channel, so responses fail to send. Let me check the session routing configuration to see if there's a mismatch between how web UI sessions and Feishu-triggered sessions are handled.\n\nLooking at the tts account config, it's using `connectionMode: websocket` which means it maintains a persistent WebSocket connection to Feishu for receiving events. This is different from webhook mode. The issue might be that the WebSocket connection for the tts account isn't properly authenticated or subscribed to the right message events in Feishu.\n\nI should check if there are any connection errors in the logs specifically for the tts WebSocket, and also verify that the tts bot has the correct permissions in Feishu's app configuration. Another angle is to look at the `sessionKey` format to see if there's a mismatch in how messages from the tts account are being routed back.\n\nWait, let me reconsider. If the OpenClaw web UI can successfully send messages to the tts bot and receive responses, that means the tts bot is actively listening and able to respond. So the issue isn't with the bot itself—it's specifically that Feishu messages aren't reaching it. This suggests a routing problem: either the Feishu app is configured to use a different callback URL, or there's something wrong with the webhook or WebSocket subscription for that particular app.\n\nLooking at the user's description again, they mentioned the message goes through but there's no reply, which is different from an error. When a user sends a message to the TK bot in Feishu, the app_id gets included in the request, and OpenClaw uses that to route to the correct account handler. If the routing is working but responses aren't being sent back, the problem could be in the response path or the message handling pipeline itself. The fact that the cron job can execute and send messages using the feishu_im_user_message tool proves the tts account has valid credentials and can send messages successfully. This suggests the issue might be with how the bot processes incoming messages - perhaps it's receiving them but failing to generate responses due to a timeout, deserialization error, or missing required context. I should check if there's a recent error log in the tts agent's sessions that shows a failed message processing attempt, and also examine the cron event configuration to understand how messages are supposed to be routed back to the user.\n\nLooking at the message structure from the cron job, it explicitly instructs the agent to \"Use the message tool if you need to notify the user directly for the current chat.\" This means the bot knows it should use feishu_im_user_message to respond. Yet when the user sends a direct message to the TK bot in Feishu, there's no reply - which suggests either the incoming message isn't being routed to the agent at all, or the agent isn't triggering the notification flow for direct user messages the way it does for cron events. The fact that the user can successfully chat with TK in the OpenClaw web UI confirms the bot is functional. This rules out token or MCP configuration issues. The problem seems specific to how Feishu routes messages to the bot, or how the bot responds to Feishu messages, versus how it handles web UI interactions.\n\nI'm considering two possibilities: either the tts session is locked from the cron job and can't process new messages, or there's a routing issue where Feishu delivers the message but the response never gets sent back through the same Feishu channel. The cron job uses feishu_im_user_message, so a new user message should theoretically trigger a new session. But if the session is somehow stuck or if there's a mismatch between how messages are received versus how responses are sent back via Feishu, that could explain the issue.\n\nLet me think about this differently. When a Feishu message arrives for the tts account, OpenClaw should route it to the tts agent for processing. The agent responds, and the response needs to go back through the tts account's Feishu connection - specifically through the feishu_im_user_message tool which uses the user identity token. The problem might be that the response is being sent via the user token instead of the bot's own token, or there's a disconnect in how the message gets routed back to the original sender in Feishu.\n\nActually, I should reconsider the routing entirely. Each Feishu app has its own bot token, and when a message comes in on one app's connection, the response should go out through that same app's token - not a different one. If the tts account is set up correctly with its own app_id and token, then responses should route properly. But maybe the issue is that when a user sends a message to the TK bot in Feishu, something in the routing or session management is preventing the response from being sent back through the correct channel.\n\nLet me check the sessions API to see if there are any active sessions for the tts account and what their message queues look like. I should also verify the tts account configuration directly to confirm the app_id and token are actually set and active.\n\nLooking at what I know: the bot itself is registered and connected, the OpenClaw web UI can communicate with it, but Feishu messages aren't getting responses. This suggests the bot can receive messages through OpenClaw's API but not through Feishu's webhook. The issue is likely that the Feishu app's webhook isn't properly configured or the bot token isn't being used correctly when OpenClaw tries to send responses back through Feishu.\n\nLet me check the recent logs to see what's actually happening when Feishu messages come in. I should also consider whether the allowFrom configuration might be interfering with message delivery, or if there's something about how the bot's Feishu connection is set up that's preventing it from receiving or responding to messages through that channel.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the session handling. If the tts bot has `allowFrom: [\"ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb\"]` and the user's open_id matches, the message should be allowed through. But maybe there's a session concurrency issue where a previous job is still occupying the bot's processing capacity. Let me check the gateway status to see what's currently running on the tts account and whether there are any blocked or queued jobs preventing it from responding to new messages.\n","thinkingSignature":"19c6182f416bad03a8f8dbf97f01f41e440602aa466ebf2e5be63ce83b68f2d0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xapux743lu4n_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /home/halei/.openclaw/agents/tts/sessions/ | head -10 && echo \"---\" && python3 -c \"\nimport json\nwith open('/home/halei/.openclaw/agents/tts/sessions/sessions.json') as f:\n    data = json.load(f)\nsessions = data if isinstance(data, list) else data.get('sessions', [])\nprint(f'Total sessions: {len(sessions)}')\n# show status of sessions\nfor s in sessions[:3]:\n    print(json.dumps(s, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)[:500])\n\" 2>/dev/null","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":90942,"output":2538,"cacheRead":256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":93736,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779537872136,"responseId":"0660cad09754172b5e57bd7778cbc02d"}}
