{"type":"message","id":"4f9995bf","parentId":"eb3a0902","timestamp":"2026-05-23T12:10:49.605Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the last message from tts at `[2026-05-23T01:02:27.318Z]` was an empty assistant response with an error: `\"stopReason\":\"error\",\"errorMessage\":\"{\\\"type\\\":\\\"error\\\",\\\"error\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"overloaded_error\\\",\\\"message\\\":\\\"server is busy, please retry later\\\"}}\"`\n\nSo the tts agent encountered an overloaded error at 01:02:27 and produced an empty response. This might have left the session in a bad state.\n\nThen the user is messaging from Feishu. The message is going to the kiit session (the current conversation). But they say they're messaging TK 选品大师 directly in Feishu.\n \nWait - I'm realizing the user's actual Feishu message might have been to TK bot, but since I'm in this conversation with them right now, those messages are getting routed to kiit's session instead of creating a new tts session. The tts agent also has an active webchat session that was updated over 2 hours ago (at 10:24), but that's separate from the Feishu messages. The cron job ran fine at 9AM this morning with tts actively processing, so the system was working then.\n\nThe user is being clear though - other agents work fine, only TK 选品大师 has this issue, and it works in the web UI but not in Feishu. The problem isn't the agent itself or the OpenClaw routing since other agents work fine in Feishu. The tts account is configured correctly for allowFrom and dmPolicy with the user's open_id, so the issue must be specific to how Feishu messages are being delivered to that bot account.\n\nLooking at the Feishu app_id for TK (cli_a930f78f51399bc6) - when the user sends a message to this bot in Feishu, the message should come through the WebSocket connection to OpenClaw, which then routes it to the tts agent. The issue might be in how the WebSocket connection handles incoming messages for this particular bot, or the routing logic isn't properly directing the message to the tts agent after it's received.\n\nI'm trying to figure out if there's something specific about the tts session configuration that differs from kiit. The kiit agent works fine when receiving Feishu messages, but tts doesn't respond - they should be similar setups in OpenClaw, so why would one work and not the other?\n\nLooking at the session data, there's `agent:tts:main` which is the webchat session (updated 10:24), and `agent:tts:feishu:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` which doesn't exist yet (the user has never messaged tts from Feishu). The cron session also updated today at 9AM. So the question is whether tts has the proper configuration to receive Feishu messages through the kiit account's channel.\n\nActually, I'm realizing I might be looking at this wrong - in Feishu's multi-bot architecture, each bot has its own webhook endpoint, and the way OpenClaw routes incoming messages to the correct bot depends on which app_id the message is addressed to. When a user sends a message to the TK bot, Feishu delivers it to that bot's webhook, and OpenClaw should route it to the tts agent. The issue might be that the kiit account is handling kiit's messages while the tts account's WebSocket connection is somehow not receiving the TK bot's incoming messages properly.\n\nBut wait - I just realized something from the screenshots. The user sent me a screenshot of the tts / main session in the OpenClaw web UI, but that's the webchat interface, not the Feishu DM. So they're showing me that the tts agent works in webchat, not that it's actively receiving Feishu messages. If they had messaged TK bot in Feishu and it worked, they'd be showing me the Feishu conversation, not the web UI. This means either they haven't actually tested messaging TK bot in Feishu yet, or they tested it but it didn't create a new Feishu session for tts. I should ask them directly if they've tried sending a message to TK bot in Feishu since our fix.\n\nWait, I'm also noticing the sessions.json shows an active tts webchat session (agent:tts:main) with an updatedAt of 1779537871917, which is around 10:24 AM based on the current time of 20:04. That's about 10 hours ago, so this session is still alive but hasn't received any messages in the last 10 hours. The cron run at 9AM did execute and process the daily selection job, so tts is functioning - it's just the Feishu integration that's not creating the expected session when messages come in through Feishu instead of the webchat interface.\n\nThe core issue seems to be that while the tts agent is operational (it's handling the cron job fine), it's not picking up sessions from Feishu messages the way kiit does. When a user sends a message through Feishu to kiit, it creates a persistent session that allows back-and-forth conversation, but that mechanism isn't working for tts - I need to figure out why the routing differs between these two integrations.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a difference in how each bot's app is configured in Feishu's developer console, or if the tts bot is in a state where it receives messages but can't respond because the allowFrom policy is blocking them. Let me walk the user through a concrete test to see what's actually happening when they message the TK bot - whether they're getting a delivery failure or just silence.\n\nBut actually, I'm realizing I should check the gateway logs more carefully. There's a journalctl entry showing tts processing a request around 20:04, which suggests the bot might be receiving messages through the MCP tool call rather than through the Feishu webhook directly - that could explain why it's not responding the normal way. The MCP tool call is `feishu_task_agent` for registration, which is separate from message handling. Let me look more carefully at what logs exist for incoming Feishu messages to understand how they're being routed to the tts session.\n\nI'm considering whether the tts account might need its own webhook path since having multiple accounts share the same endpoint could be causing issues. But more likely, the problem might be simpler - when the user sends a message to the TK bot in Feishu, it's being delivered but the response isn't making it back, possibly due to a session conflict or the tts agent being occupied. Let me ask the user directly: can they send a message right now to the TK bot and tell me exactly what happens - does it show sent, does it error, does the bot simply not respond? That'll help me pinpoint whether this is a delivery issue or something else.\n\nWait, I should also verify the Feishu app configuration for the TK bot. The app_id `cli_a930f78f51399bc6` needs to have the correct webhook and event subscriptions configured in the Feishu developer console, and the bot needs to be properly set up there. Let me ask the user to confirm the app is set up correctly on the Feishu side.\n\nBut actually, there's another possibility I should explore - maybe the TK bot's Feishu app is installed, but the user account authorization (OAuth) for the TK bot has expired or was never completed in the first place. This could explain why the bot isn't responding. Let me check if the user completed the authorization flow for the TK app.\n","thinkingSignature":"24809dc9c8d60519aac91cc57684592a8d6565c2a9e2598c8cac694bbaf49a6b"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n图片看到了，配置是正确的。让我查一下 TK bot 在飞书那边的安装/授权状态。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qo9gmopi528h_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/halei/.openclaw/agents/tts/sessions/sessions.json 2>/dev/null | python3 -c \"\nimport json, sys\ndata = json.load(sys.stdin)\nfor k, v in data.items():\n    print(f'Session key: {k}')\n    print(f'  origin: {v.get(\\\"origin\\\")}')\n    print(f'  updatedAt: {v.get(\\\"updatedAt\\\")}')\n    print(f'  lastMessagePreview: {str(v.get(\\\"lastMessagePreview\\\", \\\"\\\"))[:200]}')\n    print()\n\" 2>/dev/null","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropi