{"type":"message","id":"78d7b70c","parentId":"f65304d5","timestamp":"2026-05-23T12:13:08.700Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No output from that grep. The logging level might be \"warn\" in the config, so INFO messages aren't being logged. Let me check the log level and see if I can enable more verbose logging for feishu.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be simpler to understand. Let me re-read the evidence:\n\n1. The user sends a message to TK 选品大师 in Feishu (app_id: cli_a930f78f51399bc6)\n2. No reply\n3. The kiit bot (cli_a93650c6fc785bce) works fine - all other agents work\n4. In OpenClaw's own web UI, TK 选品大师 can respond\n\n\n5. The allowFrom and dmPolicy have been configured correctly, and the sessions.json shows there's an active session with the correct origin for the TK bot\n\nThe bot appears properly configured but messages still aren't reaching it, which suggests the issue might be elsewhere.\n\nLooking at the sessions more carefully, the most recent one at 1779537871917 (~20:04 today) is actually a webchat session (origin: webchat), not Feishu. The Feishu session for TK shows an older timestamp from May 18. This suggests messages sent via Feishu to TK either aren't creating new sessions or aren't being routed to the existing one - they might be falling into a black hole somewhere in the routing layer.\n\nSince the user said it still doesn't work after the fix, either they haven't tested the new session yet, or the new messages are being rejected at the policy level. With allowFrom and dmPolicy configured correctly, new messages from the user should go through, but I should verify how the allowFrom field is actually being evaluated against the sender's identity.\n\nWait - looking at the screenshot again, the white list shows `ou_f590c429...` but the session origin uses `feishu:ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68`. The user HALEI has open_id `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb`, yet the only Feishu session for tts has `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` - which doesn't match. This mismatch could mean the allowFrom configuration isn't matching the actual sender's identity properly.\n\nThe user was saying it still doesn't work after the fix, so they're likely testing the scenario where they send a message to TK 选品大师 and nothing happens. Since there's no active Feishu session for the user's current identity with tts, the message might be getting lost somewhere in the routing or policy enforcement layer.\n\nI should just try sending a message directly to the user to see if that works, which would confirm the basic messaging infrastructure is functional.\n\nBut wait - the kiit bot definitely works since the user has been talking to it, so maybe the real issue is that the user doesn't realize they need to explicitly open a conversation with TK 选品大师 in Feishu rather than just messaging kiit. When they tried to contact TK directly and got no response, that could be a routing problem where the TK bot's events aren't being processed correctly. Let me check if the TK bot's websocket connection is actually active and receiving events properly.\n\nActually, I'm noticing something important in the logs - I see feishu messages coming through for kiit but nothing for tts. This could mean either the feishu plugin isn't receiving tts events, or the events are being received but silently filtered out. The fact that the screenshot shows \"绑定正常\" suggests the bot is configured, but maybe the events aren't actually arriving at the right endpoint. I'm realizing the issue might be in how feishu determines which account to use when delivering messages—if it only looks at the app_id from the JWT token rather than respecting the bot_id in the event itself, then all messages would route to the same account regardless of which bot they were sent to. The token validation process might be the culprit here. The session key format suggests OpenClaw uses `agent:tts:feishu:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` for user messages, but in the sessions file I only see `agent:tts:feishu:direct:ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68`. Since the user's open_id is `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb`, a session with that open_id should exist but it's missing from the sessions list—there's only `agent:tts:main` and the cron session, so the Feishu DM session for the user isn't showing up at all.\n\nThe fact that the user reported the problem yesterday but there's no corresponding session in the logs is significant. Either the messages were rejected before reaching the session layer, or they're being routed to kiit instead of tts due to an account mismatch. Given that the user is confirmed as `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` and allowed by the policy, I should try sending a message directly to the TK bot through the feishu_im_user_message tool to test if outbound messaging works—if that succeeds, it would confirm the account is properly configured and the problem is specifically with inbound message handling.\n\nBut wait, that tool uses the user's identity, not the bot's, so it wouldn't actually validate the bot's send capability. I need to think about this differently—maybe I should ask the user to clarify whether they're messaging the correct bot in Feishu and check if messages are being delivered to the correct account or falling into the default account.\n\nActually, I think the core issue might be simpler: when the user sends a message to TK bot on Feishu, if the TK app isn't properly configured with its webhook or event subscription, Feishu might be routing those messages to the default kiit account instead. The kiit account has `allowFrom: ou_f590c429...` and `dmPolicy: allowlist`, so it would accept messages from that user—but they're going to the wrong bot.\n\nSince both accounts use the same webhook endpoint, the problem likely isn't at the network level but rather in how Feishu routes messages when the TK app's event subscription isn't correctly set up. I should suggest checking the TK app's event subscription configuration in the Feishu developer console.\n\nActually, wait—the user confirmed that in OpenClaw's own web UI, TK can reply. So the agent itself works. The issue is specifically when messaging through Feishu, not the web UI. This suggests the problem is with Feishu message delivery or routing, not the agent's functionality.\n\nLet me step back and consider what I know for certain: TK's Feishu account is configured with the correct allowFrom and dmPolicy settings, the account is enabled, the appId is correct, and the user has been whitelisted. The agent worked on May 22 at 20:08:24 when a message was sent, but there's been nothing since then despite the user saying it still doesn't work. The most recent session is webchat-based from today at 20:04.\n\nSince the user is reporting issues but I don't see new Feishu sessions for tts, they either haven't tested the new configuration yet or messages are getting lost somewhere in the routing or delivery process. Looking at that May 22 message about allowFrom being fixed, it was sent to ou_11f95142ee4622f42acc029c870f68bb, not the user itself. The user's open_id is ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb, so I need to trace where that original fix message actually went and whether it reached the right person. to different accounts? That doesn't make sense unless the user was testing from a different Feishu account, though they claim only one. I'm going in circles here—I should just ask the user to try sending a message to TK and check if the WebSocket connection shows activity in the logs.\n","thinkingSignature":"c4ca74908f32fc8576d55b843190b692af290ae52b04569ab68b1fefc3ac9067"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_p0dqn7wel0rr_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 100 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep -E \"cli_a930|cli_a936\" | head -20","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":100,"outpu