{"type":"message","id":"ceb8bb34","parentId":"c142514b","timestamp":"2026-05-23T12:17:50.832Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The gateway.log shows that both kiit and tts connected via WebSocket on May 5th, and then there was a restart on May 15th. But the May 15th startup log doesn't show the feishu connections being re-established. Let me check the gateway.log for the May 15th startup to see if the feishu[tts] websocket connected successfully.Let me look at the gateway.log around May 15 20:52 when the gateway restarted to see if tts websocket started properly.\n\nActually, looking at the error log, I see that on May 15th the log ends at `[2026-05-15T20:52:39.710Z][33m[agents/auth-profiles][39m [33mignored invalid auth profile entries during store load[39m`. \n\nThere's nothing after that, which could mean the log got truncated or the process ended unexpectedly. But since the gateway is running now with PID 499639, it's clearly alive. The log was last written on May 15th at 20:52, and the current time is May 23rd at 20:17, so there's a gap - the gateway process crashed and restarted multiple times in that period.\n\nActually, looking at the startup messages - `[ClawPanel] Starting Gateway on Linux...` on May 15th - this was the clawpanel starting the gateway, not openclaw itself. The clawpanel (`/home/halei/clawpanel/scripts/serve.js`) runs openclaw and monitors it. So the current gateway PID 499639 was likely started by clawpanel.\n\nThe log file doesn't have recent entries because the current gateway process (running since May 22) is writing to journalctl instead of the gateway.log file, which explains why the file hasn't been updated since May 15th.\n\nLooking at the journalctl output from the beginning of this conversation, I can see the gateway is actively processing messages and has sessions running. The feishu plugin is clearly functional since kiit can receive messages, so the issue is likely specific to tts. I should check whether tts's WebSocket connection is actually established and receiving events, which would show up in the current gateway process logs.\n\nThe user's note about the bot working fine in the webUI but not in Feishu direct messages is key - it suggests the tts agent is responsive through clawpanel but not through Feishu's DM channel. This points to a routing problem specific to the Feishu DM integration, which could mean either the WebSocket connection for tts isn't active, the dmPolicy allowlist isn't matching the sender, or there's a webhook routing issue.\n\nI'm going to try a different approach and add some diagnostic logging to see what's actually happening when messages come in. But first, let me ask the user to test again after our restart and capture the exact behavior - whether the message gets delivered to tts at all, whether it's routed to kiit instead, or whether it fails silently. I should also check the tts session to see if there's any indication of what might be blocking the message flow.\n\nWait - I think I found the real issue. Looking at the gateway.log from May 5th, both kiit and tts have the same webhook URL configured. This means they're both trying to use the same endpoint, which could be causing a conflict where kiit is intercepting tts's messages. The duplicate plugin error is also a red flag - the feishu plugin is being loaded twice from different paths, which might be causing the routing to break.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the config, the duplicate is just a warning and shouldn't affect routing by itself. The real question is whether tts's WebSocket connection is even active right now. Since kiit works, the feishu plugin is clearly running, but tts might have dropped its connection and isn't reconnecting properly. Let me check if tts has the right dmPolicy configuration - it should be \"allowlist\" with the user's open_id in allowFrom, and kiit might not have that set which would explain why kiit isn't responding.\n\nLet me reconsider the routing: when a message arrives at the gateway's webhook endpoint from Feishu, the app_id in the payload tells the gateway which account to use. But there's a discrepancy in the sessions - the tts account shows `ou_09c92e096986a0fcd5b389561a0a1a84` as its bot open_id, yet a message the user sent on May 22 at 16:08 came from `cli_a93650c6fc785bce` (kiit's app), which doesn't match the tts account being discussed.\n\nThe user is asking if the problem is fixed, and I realize I haven't actually tested whether the restart resolved the WebSocket connection issue. I should ask them to try sending a message to the TK bot again so I can see if it works now.\n\nWait, looking at the timestamp more carefully - the user is asking about 5.20, which is the version number (metadata.lastTouchedVersion: \"2026.5.20\"), not a date. So the issue has been present since that version was deployed. The question is whether the restart actually fixed the WebSocket connection for tts.\n\nI should ask the user to try sending a message to the TK bot again so I can observe what happens. But before that, let me try a more direct diagnostic approach - I'll send a test message to the TK bot myself using the tts agent's message tool to see if it can actually receive and process messages.\n\nActually, I can't send directly as the bot since that would require bot identity. Instead, I should check the feishu plugin documentation for diagnostic commands, or look at whether there's an issue with how OpenClaw is routing the tts bot's responses back to the Feishu channel. The problem might be that the bot can process messages internally but the WebSocket connection for sending responses isn't working properly.\n\nLet me just ask the user to send a test message to TK 选品大师 so I can see what happens in the logs, and also check if tts has an active session key that shows it's processing something.\n\nWait, I think I see it now. The tts session list only has 3 entries with `agent:tts:main` having the most recent timestamp (1779537871917), which corresponds to 10:44 today. But that's the webUI/main session, not a Feishu DM session. When the user sends a message to the TK bot via Feishu DM, it should create a new session `agent:tts:feishu:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb`, but that doesn't exist. This confirms that tts is not receiving Feishu DM messages at all, not even creating new sessions. The issue is likely that the WebSocket connection from OpenClaw to Feishu for the tts account isn't receiving events, or the events aren't being routed correctly to the tts agent.\n\nI should recommend asking the user to send a test message to the TK bot and watch the journalctl logs in real-time to see if the feishu[tts] channel receives anything. But before that, let me try something different - I'll send a message to the tts agent directly using sessions_send to see if the agent itself is functional and can reply, which would tell us if the issue is with the Feishu event reception or with the agent itself.\n","thinkingSignature":"7a58359792fc867cdce3e2715b9f5f25f20ba986597744f4d261dde1170c13bc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9v23x8d1oxgt_1","name":"sessions_send","arguments":{"agentId":"tts","message":"你好，这是测试消息。收到请回复\"收到\"。","timeoutSeconds":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":4118,"output":1609,"cacheRead":105993,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":111720,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779538646148,"responseId":"0660cdd6cd5d99edb4f8a6a647abc45d"}}
