{"type":"message","id":"4f8b0fe2","parentId":"7744ba98","timestamp":"2026-05-23T12:29:07.873Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is pointing out something strange in the monitoring dashboard. Let me analyze the image.\n\nKey observations from the screenshot:\n1. Multiple agents are listed: `agent:main:main`, `agent:ops:main`, `agent:finance:main`, `agent:review:main`\n2. There's an entry `agent:tts:main` that is underlined in red\n3. The age is 22m (22 minutes)\n4. The cache rate is 84%\n5. Tokens show 75k/204k\n\nWait - this is interesting. The `agent:tts:main` session has an age of 22 minutes. But I checked earlier and the tts session `agent:tts:main` had `updatedAt=1779537871917`. \n\nLet me convert the current time vs the session update time. The current time is around 20:28 GMT+8 (May 23, 2026). The updatedAt timestamp 1779537871917 is in milliseconds - let me calculate what that represents.\n\nActually, let me look at the image description more carefully. The user says \"你看这个是不是有点奇诡\" - \"do you find this strange?\"\n\nThe `agent:tts:main` being highlighted in red with age=22m could be meaningful. It means the tts agent has an active session that's 22 minutes old (since ~20:06). \n\nBut earlier I saw that `agent:tts:main` had `updatedAt=1779537871917`. Let me check the current time vs this timestamp.\n\nActually, the more important observation is: the dashboard shows `agent:tts:main` as an active session with age 22m. This means the tts agent IS running and has an active session. The session might be from when I restarted the gateway earlier, or from some other activity.\n\nBut wait - the user's message said they sent a DM to TK at 19:54 and got no reply. \n\nNow I'm seeing `agent:tts:main` with a 22-minute age. The gateway restart happened at 20:16, so that's not the source. The cron job was at 09:00. If this is from the user's message at 19:54, something might have created a tts session after all. But I don't see `agent:tts:feishu:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` in the sessions.json, which is puzzling.\n\nLet me check what this dashboard actually shows - it might be displaying active sessions across all agents. The `age=22m` suggests the tts session started around 20:06. Could this be the 20:04 message I sent earlier through kiit? No, that was in the kiit session, not tts. Actually, when I tried sending a test message to tts with sessions_send, that returned \"forbidden\" due to agent-to-agent messaging being disabled. So what's creating this tts session?\n\nLooking at the image more carefully - `agent:tts:main` appears in the system health dashboard with an age of 22 minutes, underlined in red. This might just be a UI indicator for something specific. The user is asking if this looks strange, and the red underline on a 22-minute-old tts session is definitely suspicious since that session shouldn't exist according to what I'm seeing.\n\nThe dashboard is likely showing OpenClaw's internal monitoring of active agent sessions. I should pull the actual tts session state from sessions.json to see what's really going on, since something initiated this session and I need to understand what triggered it.\n","thinkingSignature":"8b0b1b694f07f64055139baea4e205ff690aae37faafce7e79113a0213a76c0a"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n这张图很关键！`agent:tts:main` 有活跃 session，年龄 22 分钟，cache 84%。\n\n让我核实一下当前 tts 的 session 状态：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_iakrwspuffsg_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/halei/.openclaw/agents/tts/sessions/sessions.json | python3 -c \"\nimport json, sys, datetime\ndata = json.load(sys.stdin)\nprint('tts 所有 session:')\nfor k, v in data.items():\n    ts = v.get('updatedAt', 0)\n    age_ms = (datetime.datetime.now().timestamp() * 1000) - ts\n    age_min = age_ms / 60000\n    print(f'  {k}')\n    print(f'    updatedAt: {ts} ({age_min:.1f} min ago)')\n    print(f'    origin: {v.get(\\\"origin\\\")}')\n    print()\n\"","timeout":5}}],"a