{"type":"message","id":"0997f61e","parentId":"9ddfd15b","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:12:40.101Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying TK still doesn't respond, while all other bots are working. This is very strange. Let me think about what's happening:\n\n1. The tts account config is back in openclaw.json\n2. The tts binding is in place\n3. But there's still no tts feishu session for the user (ou_f590c429)\n4. The tts bot still doesn't respond\n\nLet me check what the actual feishu[tts] connection status is. Maybe the WebSocket connection for tts isn't being established even though the config is there.\n\nLet me look at the gateway logs after the restart to see if feishu[tts] connected.\n","thinkingSignature":"4106b02adcb8a1646a6d263e748cada824288ef56aaac2152afb212cc3c37bb2"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_odavcftvgep8_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 200 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep -iE \"feishu\\[tts\\]|tts.*websocket|tts.*start|tts.*connect\" | tail -20","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":19863,"output":219,"cacheRead":83072,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":103154,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779541952984,"responseId":"0660dac23235f58ef91b0ad27bc326af"}}
{"type":"message","id":"69847277","parentId":"0997f61e","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:12:40.850Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_odavcftvgep8_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"5月 23 21:12:11 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:11.332+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: message om_x100b6e2e37668ca4c25f82404f6e443 in chat oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 — immediate\n5月 23 21:12:11 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:11.745+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: received message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 in oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 (p2p)\n5月 23 21:12:11 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:11.750+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: sender ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 not in DM allowlist"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":397,"aggregated":"5月 23 21:12:11 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:11.332+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: message om_x100b6e2e37668ca4c25f82404f6e443 in chat oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 — immediate\n5月 23 21:12:11 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:11.745+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: received message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 in oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 (p2p)\n5月 23 21:12:11 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:11.750+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: sender ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 not in DM allowlist","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779541960840}}
{"type":"message","id":"3db23e86","parentId":"69847277","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:13:07.133Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see it! The log shows:\n\n```\n[feishu] feishu[tts]: received message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 in oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 (p2p)\n[feishu] feishu[tts]: sender ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 not in DM allowlist\n```\n\nThis is from the OLD user `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68`, NOT from the current user `ou_f590c429`. \n\nThe user just sent a test message but there's no new log entry for `ou_f590c429`. The TK bot IS receiving messages (the old user's message was received), but it's rejecting `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` because it's not in the allowlist.\n\nBut the key issue: the current user `ou_f590c429` sent a message, and the TK bot didn't respond. The log shows no message from `ou_f590c429` being received by `feishu[tts]`.\n\nWait - there WAS a message from the current user that triggered this conversation. But that went to KIIT, not to TK.\n\nLet me check - did the user's message to TK actually reach TK's websocket? The log might be showing the message ID from the old user (ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68) which is different from the current user. But the message ID in the current message metadata is `om_x100b6e2e356d613cc3bcc782d1f02c6` and the journalctl showed `om_x100b6e2e37668ca4c25f82404f6e443` which is similar but not the same.\n\n\nThe current user's message was indeed received by feishu[tts] based on the journalctl entry showing the message at 21:12:11, but the old user `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` is being rejected because they're not in the DM allowlist. This suggests the system is checking the sender against some kind of access control list, and the old user from 2026-05-01 isn't authorized anymore.\n\nThe current user `ou_f590c429` should be in the allowlist since it was added to the global settings, but the old user's rejection suggests their session from back then is no longer valid. Since the old user's session was created with their account, that might be why they're being rejected now - the system only maintains one active session per user.\n\nLooking at the message sequence, when the current user sends a DM to TK, the Feishu side generates a new chat_id, but OpenClaw creates a session per user-account pair. The question is whether the system is properly routing the current user's new message to their existing session or if there's a mismatch between the chat_id being generated and the session being used.\n\nThe real problem might be in how Feishu delivers messages - when a user opens a DM chat with TK, the chat_id gets assigned by Feishu based on the app_id and user_id, so the same pair should always generate the same chat_id. If the system isn't recognizing that this is the same user returning to an existing conversation, it might be treating their message as a new session instead of updating the old one.\n\nLooking at the feishu[tts] logs, the system is receiving messages and routing them, but I need to see what happens after the message is delivered to feishu[tts] to understand why it's not being processed correctly.\n\nThe message from `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` was rejected because they're not in the DM allowlist, which is expected. But the current user `ou_f590c429` should be allowed through since they're in the global allowFrom list. The issue might be that when the gateway restarts, it clears the tts sessions and needs to re-establish the connection - so I should check if the feishu[tts] connection was properly restored after the restart.\n\nThe most likely culprit is that the current user's message never actually reached feishu[tts] in the first place. When a user sends a DM to the TK bot via the Feishu client, the message should be routed to feishu[tts], but if the routing or connection failed, the message just gets silently dropped. I need to verify whether the user's message actually made it to feishu[tts] by checking the logs for message ID `om_x100b6e2e356d613cc3bcc782d1f02c6` or similar entries from `ou_f590c429`.\n\nLooking at the journalctl output showing a 21:12 message from `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68`, that was the old user being rejected. But the current user's message should have been received at approximately 21:12 as well. Let me check if the tts WebSocket connection is actually active and properly established after the restart.\n\nAfter the gateway restart at 20:57, the tts account should have reconnected and established its WebSocket connection to Feishu. The connectionMode is set to \"websocket\" which should handle this automatically. However, the tts account configuration only specifies `enabled: true`, `appId`, `appSecret`, and `connectionMode: websocket`, with no additional parameters like `name` or `allowFrom`. This might indicate the tts WebSocket client isn't being properly initialized on startup.\n\nThe old session `agent:tts:feishu:direct:ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` is from a previous user that was added to the tts allowFrom at some point, but the current configuration might not be preserving that or allowing new users properly. and old). For the OLD user, the session was created, but now they're rejected (not in allowlist). For the CURRENT user `ou_f590c429`, no session exists.\n\nThe question is: did the current user's message reach feishu[tts]? Let me check if there's a way to verify.\n\nActually, let me just try to send a message to the tts agent directly using the sessions_send tool and see if it works:\n\nNo wait, sessions_send with agentId tts doesn't work because agent-to-agent messaging is disabled.\n\nLet me think about what else to check. Actually, the user said \"我可以内部测试一下，发消息给他\" - asking me to test by sending a message to TK. But I can't directly send a message to TK through the feishu channel. Let me see if there's another way.\n\nActually, I can check if the feishu[tts] WebSocket is truly connected and receiving events. Let me look at the system more carefully to understand what's happening with the event flow.\n\nWhen a user sends a DM to the TK bot, Feishu routes it through WebSocket to OpenClaw, which extracts the app_id and maps it to the tts account via the accountId in the message event. Then it checks the allowFrom allowlist to determine if the sender is permitted. If they pass that check and a routing binding exists for tts on feishu, the message should reach the tts agent.\n\nThe problem might be that the user wasn't added to the allowlist for this account initially, so their message got rejected. Looking at the error logs more carefully, I notice the user mentioned \"没有，我测试了飞书，不行还是只有 选品大师没有回复\" - they're saying they tested but the product selector isn't responding. This suggests the issue isn't with the connection itself, but rather with how the message is being processed or delivered to the tts agent.\n\nThe journalctl output shows an `immediate` message status rather than `queued`, which means the current user's message was delivered right away without waiting. But I don't see a corresponding log entry for the current user's message itself. Let me check the feishu[tts] session to see if a new session was actually created for this user, since that would indicate whether the message was properly received and processed. the current user's message IS being received, but then something goes wrong between feishu receiving it and the agent responding. Maybe the message reaches the feishu account but fails to route to the tts agent, or the tts agent receives it but something breaks before a response is sent back.\n\nActually, if the message had been queued rather than immediate, that would suggest the tts agent was already processing something. But the immediate status indicates it was delivered right away. So either the tts agent is receiving the message and failing silently, or Feishu isn't routing the user's messages to tts at all even though the old user's were. Let me focus on verifying whether Feishu is actually delivering the current user's messages to tts.\n\nThe most direct way to test this would be to send a message directly to the TK bot in Feishu myself and see if it actually responds, or check the logs for any outgoing message from tts that corresponds to the test message. Looking back at the session state, the old user has a tts feishu session from before but the current user doesn't, which means the current user's first message should have created a new session. If it didn't, then no message was received. But the immediate status suggests feishu did receive something from the current user.\n\nLet me search the logs for any rejection of the current user's ID to see if that's what's happening.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that when the gateway restarts, the tts account's WebSocket connection to Feishu needs to re-establish itself, and the allowFrom might not be properly set during reconnection. Or maybe there's a mismatch where the user is hitting the kiit account instead of tts. Let me verify what account the current user is actually associated with in the kiit account's session.\n\nIf the current user sent a message to tts, we should see a new session file created for them, but since their session doesn't exist yet, that means either tts didn't receive the message or rejected it. When I checked the sessions file after the restart, it only showed the old user's session—no new entry for the current user appeared, which is odd. I should look more carefully at the timestamp to confirm whether the current user's message actually arrived and was processed.\n\nThe current user `ou_f590c429` isn't showing up in the tts sessions at all, only `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` has one. This means no message from the current user has successfully created a session with tts. Since the user is definitely sending messages to TK and they're not being received, the issue is likely that either the message isn't reaching tts at all, or it's being rejected before a session can be created. The most probable causes are that the user's ID isn't in the tts allowlist, or the tts WebSocket connection isn't properly established and needs to be checked.\n\nWait—I should verify whether feishu[tts] even has an active connection. The gateway restarted at 20:57, but the old logs showed it was connected before. After a restart, the WebSocket should reconnect, but maybe it's not working properly now. Let me check the process list to see if there's a connection issue.\n\nActually, I already verified the tts account has `connectionMode: websocket` set explicitly, which should persist across restarts since it's defined at the account level in the config. But I'm not seeing the typical reconnection logs in journalctl. Let me try checking the sessions list directly to see if there's any feishu[tts] session activity, or test by sending a message to the TK bot directly through Feishu to see if the tts WebSocket is actually receiving events.\n\nThe user wants me to test by sending a message to TK internally, but I don't have direct access to do that—I can't control their Feishu app from here. Let me focus on the feishu[tts] connection itself. Looking at the logs around 21:12, I see a message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 to feishu[tts], but I need to verify if the current user ou_f590c429 is actually connecting to tts or if it's going to kiit instead. Let me check the current connection status of feishu[tts] to diagnose whether it's properly established or if there's a routing issue. The error message is cut off, but I can see it's complaining about an allowlist issue - the sender isn't in the DM allowlist. The old user wasn't able to send messages because they weren't on the approved list, which suggests there might be a whitelist configuration problem preventing messages from reaching tts.\n\nSince the allowlist is set to allow `ou_f590c429`, the current user should be permitted, but I need to verify if that config is actually being applied to the tts account or if it's being overridden somewhere.\n\nThe config shows tts inherits from global, which has `allowFrom: ['ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb']` and `dmPolicy: allowlist`, so the current user should be allowed. The old user isn't in the allowlist, so they're correctly being rejected.\n\nThe real issue might be that the tts WebSocket connection to Feishu isn't actually receiving events. I should verify if the tts connection is still active and properly established after the gateway restart.\n\nI could test this by triggering a session creation manually—using `sessions_send` to ping the tts agent would create a new message event and verify the connection works. But I realize I'm getting stuck in a loop here. The most direct approach is to ask the user to send a test message to TK and immediately tell me whether it arrives or not, so I can confirm whether the WebSocket is actually receiving events from Feishu. a message from the current user is reaching tts. Let me check if there's any entry in the logs that would show this - something like a session creation or message receipt for the current user's ID.\n\nActually, I just realized - the error log entry shows the OLD user was rejected. But it also shows feishu[tts] RECEIVED that message. So feishu[tts] IS receiving messages! If it's receiving messages from the old user, it should receive messages from the current user too (assuming the current user's ID is in the allowlist).\n\nThe current user's ID (ou_f590c429) IS in the global allowlist, so feishu[tts] should accept their messages too. But the user says TK is not responding to their messages. So either the messages are not reaching feishu[tts], or feishu[tts] is receiving them but not processing them correctly.\n\nWait - maybe the issue is that the user's message to TK is going through kiit's account instead? When a user opens a DM with the TK bot in Feishu, the message goes to TK's app_id. But if for some reason the message is being routed to kiit's app instead... but that doesn't make sense because each app_id is distinct.\n\nActually, I'm not sure what's happening. Let me try a different approach. Let me check if the user's messages to TK are even reaching OpenClaw by looking at the inbound message logs more carefully. Or maybe I should just look at the gateway logs to see what account the current user's messages are actually going to.\n\nLet me ask the user to check the TK bot's allowFrom configuration to make sure the current user is in there, and also verify the event subscription is still active. Actually, I already verified that. Let me just look at the gateway logs to see what's happening with the current user's messages to TK. Maybe there's a routing issue or the messages aren't being received at all. Let me check the raw gateway logs to see if there's anything about the current user's messages or any errors in receiving them. The error log shows feishu[tts] received a message but rejected it because the sender wasn't in the DM allowlist. That's actually a good sign - it means feishu[tts] is actively receiving messages. Since the old user got rejected for not being in the allowlist, the current user's message would likely be accepted since they're in the global allowFrom list. So the current user's message should be received and processed.\n\nBut maybe the issue is that when the current user's message arrives, something else is going wrong. Let me check what happens in the logs after the message is received - whether there's any error during processing or routing to the agent. The most likely culprit is that while feishu[tts] is connected, it's only receiving the old user's messages and not the current user's messages at all.\n\nWait - that doesn't make sense. The old user's messages are being rejected because they're not in the allowlist, so if feishu[tts] is receiving those, it should receive the current user's messages too. Unless the current user is sending messages to a different account entirely. Let me check what account the current user's messages are actually going to by looking at the sessions. The kiit session `agent:main:feishu:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` exists, so maybe the current user's messages are being routed to kiit instead of tts.\n\nNo wait - the user is saying they sent a message to TK directly and got no response. That message should go to TK's app_id. Let me verify by checking the session mapping again: when the user opens TK's app in Feishu and sends a message, the recipient app_id should be TK's (cli_a930f78f51399bc6), not kiit's. But the current user doesn't have a tts session at all, which means either the message is never reaching tts, or tts is rejecting it somehow. I need to look at what the tts account's allowFrom configuration actually shows.\n\nThe config is inherited from global settings, so allowFrom should include ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb. But the previous tts configuration had allowFrom set explicitly at the tts level too - though when I checked right after restart, it was None. This discrepancy suggests the tts account's allowFrom might not be inheriting correctly from global, or it's being overridden somewhere. Let me trace through the gateway logs to see if there's a warning about the tts account's allowFrom configuration.\n\nActually, I should just try explicitly adding the current user to tts's allowFrom to ensure they're whitelisted. But I need to verify whether tts has its own allowFrom or is relying on global. Looking back at the config structure, I see tts doesn't have an explicit allowFrom set - it's inheriting from global. But the current user said their messages aren't reaching tts at all, not even being rejected, which suggests either the message isn't reaching tts or tts isn't responding to the current user's allowFrom check.\n\nLet me check the journalctl logs around 21:12 when the user sent their test message to see if there's any feishu[tts] activity or error related to the current user.\n","thinkingSignature":"8a59b69c8e420ff32be5b43f5be099472e2ea9ff6b667bfa30a0175234d7f6a6"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_019l46frb924_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 500 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep -iE \"ou_f590c429.*tts|tts.*ou_f590c429|ou_f590c429.*feishu|feishu.*ou_f590c429\" | tail -20","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":398,"output":4205,"cacheRead":102912,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":107515,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779541961151,"responseId":"0660dac9c5171579a8ed9db669da9c2b"}}
{"type":"message","id":"4e7fcf0d","parentId":"3db23e86","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:13:07.402Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_019l46frb924_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"5月 23 21:12:27 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:27.192+08:00 [feishu] feishu[default]: received message from ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb in oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8 (p2p)\n5月 23 21:12:31 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:31.196+08:00 [mcp] registerTool ctx: sessionKey=\"agent:main:feishu:default:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb\", messageChannel=\"feishu\", requesterSenderId=\"ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb\", agentAccountId=\"default\", sessionChat=undefined"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":58,"aggregated":"5月 23 21:12:27 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:27.192+08:00 [feishu] feishu[default]: received message from ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb in oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8 (p2p)\n5月 23 21:12:31 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[521949]: 2026-05-23T21:12:31.196+08:00 [mcp] registerTool ctx: sessionKey=\"agent:main:feishu:default:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb\", messageChannel=\"feishu\", requesterSenderId=\"ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb\", agentAccountId=\"default\", sessionChat=undefined","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779541987399}}
{"type":"message","id":"d5ac395c","parentId":"4e7fcf0d","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:13:17.472Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the problem clearly:\n\n1. At 21:12:11, the feishu[tts] received a message from `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` (NOT the current user ou_f590c429), and it was rejected because \"sender ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 not in DM allowlist\"\n\n2. At 21:12:27, the feishu[default] received a message from `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` (the current user), and this went to the default account (kiit), not to tts\n\nSo the problem is:\n- The user's messages to TK are going to feishu[default] instead of feishu[tts]\n- This means the message routing is NOT using the tts account even though the user sent to TK's appId (cli_a930f78f51399bc6)\n\nWhy is the user's message going to default instead of tts?\n\nThe user confirmed that they sent the message to TK's app (app_id: cli_a930f78f51399bc6). So Feishu should deliver it to the correct app. But somehow it's going to the default account.\n\nWait - let me think about this. When the user opens a DM with TK in Feishu:\n1. Feishu shows the chat with TK's app\n2. User sends a message\n3. Feishu delivers the message to TK's webhook/websocket\n4. OpenClaw receives it and... routes it?\n\nBut the log shows it went to `feishu[default]`. This means OpenClaw is receiving the message but routing it to the wrong account.\n\nHmm, but wait - if the user opened the TK chat in Feishu, the message should be addressed to TK's appId. So why is it going to default?\n \nMaybe TK's websocket connection isn't actually receiving messages, or Feishu is delivering to a different endpoint than expected. Or perhaps the routing logic in OpenClaw is matching based on something other than the appId - like the sender's identity or some other factor that's causing it to route to the default account instead of tts.\n\nLooking at the binding structure, the tts route should match when both the accountId is \"tts\" and the channel is \"feishu\". But the fact that it's landing on \"default\" suggests the binding isn't being applied correctly, or there's a fallback happening when the tts binding fails to match. Let me trace through what accountId is actually being assigned when this message arrives.\n\nThe user's message is coming through as `feishu[default]` with the sender ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb. The metadata shows it's a direct message to user:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb, which doesn't match how the tts binding is structured. I need to figure out why feishu[default] is being used instead of the explicitly configured feishu[tts] account when the user sends to TK's appId.\n\nFeishu delivers messages to the webhook URL configured for each app, but if multiple apps share the same endpoint, there's an ambiguity problem. The global feishu channel has connectionMode: websocket, so events come through WebSocket rather than webhook. When the TK app receives a message in Feishu, it should route to the feishu[tts] account through the WebSocket connection, but it's ending up on feishu[default] instead.\n\nThe issue might be that the TK app's WebSocket connection isn't properly established or the routing logic isn't matching the account correctly. When I restarted the gateway, the feishu[tts] websocket should have connected, but I need to verify it's actually connected and not falling back to the default account. Let me check the logs after restart to see if feishu[tts] successfully established its connection.","thinkingSignature":"c1524f03b3ee8931f5adf71bba4165b4c59919b16ed68b25bff6af764668d80e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5z2k7jd3054j_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 500 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | tail -50","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":343,"output":909,"cacheRead":103296,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":104548,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779541987737,"responseId":"0660dae4fd144ebc23b82d2bfda771b0"}}
