{"type":"message","id":"88c44b61","parentId":"c67c67f2","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:41:59.541Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to understand why the user's message to TK is going to kiit instead of tts.\n\nLooking at the flow:\n1. User sends DM to TK bot (appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6)\n2. Feishu delivers the message to OpenClaw\n3. OpenClaw should route to feishu[tts] account\n4. But instead it goes to feishu[kiit]\n\nThe issue might be in how OpenClaw routes incoming Feishu messages. When Feishu delivers a message for appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6, OpenClaw needs to match this appId to the tts account.\n\nBut wait - looking at the `defaultAccount: kiit` in the config. This might mean that when OpenClaw can't match the appId to a specific account, it falls back to defaultAccount (kiit). But tts IS configured as an account...Unless the tts account configuration isn't being loaded properly because it was added manually to the JSON file (not through the proper config mechanism) and the Gateway is ignoring it.\n\nActually, let me look at the config again. The tts account is there with appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6. But the Gateway might be reading it wrong.\n\nOr maybe the issue is that when a Feishu message comes in, the Gateway uses the appId from the message to look up the account. If it can't find the account by appId, it falls back to defaultAccount.\n\nLet me check if the tts account is actually being loaded by the Gateway at startup. Looking at the log output from the earlier restart:\n```\n[feishu] starting feishu[kiit] (mode: websocket)\n[feishu] starting feishu[tts] (mode: websocket)\n```\n\nBoth kiit and tts were started. So the Gateway does recognize the tts account.\n\nBut wait - the restart that just happened (after my config patch adding tts) should have also started tts. \n\nI don't see any feishu[tts] startup log this time. Let me check if tts is actually connecting when the Gateway restarts.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The log shows messages going to feishu[kiit] for the user. But the user is sending to TK bot (cli_a930f78f51399bc6). So why is it going to kiit?\n\nUnless... the user is actually sending to kiit, not TK? But they said they sent to TK...\n\nOr maybe the issue is that when you send a DM to a Feishu bot, Feishu delivers it via the webhook/websocket, and the appId in the message tells the Gateway which account to use. But if the Gateway isn't properly matching appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6 to the tts account, it might be defaulting to kiit instead.\n\nLooking at the Feishu API docs, when OpenClaw creates a WebSocket connection to Feishu for each account, both kiit and tts should be connected and receiving events. When a message arrives, the Gateway should extract the appId from the message payload and route it to the correct account. But maybe Feishu isn't sending the message to the right app, or the Gateway isn't parsing the appId correctly from what Feishu sends.\n\nActually, I think the problem might be that when the user binds TK's appId in a third-party panel, it creates a persistent connection that intercepts messages before OpenClaw can route them. So when the user sends to TK's appId, the binding is already redirecting it to kiit instead of letting it reach the tts account through normal routing.\n\nBut that's not quite right either—the bindings in openclaw.json look correct. Let me check if the Gateway is actually using the bindings array or if something else is overriding it.\n\nMaybe I should try a different approach: instead of using account-based routing, I can route directly by sender ID using a peer binding. This would pin a specific user to the tts agent regardless of which appId the message appears to be from.\n\nWait, the error message shows ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 isn't in the allowlist. But ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb should be. The fact that the old user's messages are still appearing means the tts account is receiving events—the issue is just the allowlist blocking them.\n\nBut then why isn't ou_f590c429's message reaching tts? The log only shows kiit receiving it, not tts. So either ou_f590c429 is sending to the kiit bot instead of tts, or the tts WebSocket is receiving it but something else is preventing delivery.\n\nWait—the user confirmed they're sending to the TK bot with appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6. If that's true, why is kiit receiving it instead?\n\nMaybe there's a mismatch between what the user thinks they're sending to and what's actually happening. They believe they're messaging the TK bot, but the message is being routed to kiit instead. Or perhaps tk's allowFrom configuration isn't working as expected and messages are falling back to kiit.\n\nActually, looking at the message logs more carefully: when the user sends, the Gateway sees the appId (cli_a930 for tk) and routes it to feishu[tts]. But tk's allowlist blocks it. The kiit account should handle the user's message since they're in kiit's allowFrom list, so why isn't it working?\n\nUnless the Gateway isn't routing by appId at all—maybe it's routing all DMs from the user to kiit regardless of which bot they message. That would explain why tk ignores the user's message but kiit should accept it. But that contradicts what I'm seeing in the logs.\n\nOr maybe the Gateway is doing some kind of fallback routing where if tk rejects the message, it tries kiit instead. But that doesn't make sense either.\n\nLet me reconsider the possibility that the user actually IS sending to tk's bot, but the Gateway is routing it to kiit because the appId mapping is broken or the user is somehow messaging the wrong bot entirely. Actually, wait - the user said tk is bound to kiit in that third-party panel. What if that panel is actually updating OpenClaw's config to rebind tk's appId (cli_a930) to the kiit agent instead of tk? That would explain everything - the message goes to tk's appId, the Gateway routes it to kiit because of the rebinding, kiit accepts it, and then I'm responding as kiit.\n\nBut the user said they unbound it. Unless the panel has a persistent effect that's still overriding the routing even after unbinding. Or maybe there's a timing issue where the unbinding didn't fully take effect before we added the new binding.\n\nLooking at the actual bindings in openclaw.json, they show tk routing to tts and kiit routing to main, so the config looks correct. Unless the Gateway is reading it wrong or there's something else going on with how the routing is being applied.\n\nLet me try something different - maybe I should look at this from the Feishu side. The user could test whether TK's WebSocket connection is actually receiving messages. Or I could check the session storage to see what sessions exist. Actually, I notice kiit is handling my current message, which means kiit IS working. But the user is asking about TK - they're not getting responses from TK. So the issue is TK specifically isn't responding, not that nothing works.\n\nLooking at the session list, there's no session for ou_f590c429 in tts, only in kiit. This suggests the user's message to TK didn't create a tts session - it got routed to kiit instead. But kiit should be routing messages to the correct bot based on which appId they used. Unless the routing logic is inverted somewhere - like if you're messaging TK's appId but the Gateway thinks it's kiit's appId and routes it to kiit.\n\nMaybe the issue is that kiit is receiving messages sent to TK's appId because the Gateway is matching based on accountId instead of the actual appId from the message. Or maybe when the user unbinds TK from kiit and rebinds it to tts, there's some stale config causing kiit to still intercept those messages. I should try restarting the Gateway again to clear any cached state that might be causing this routing confusion.\n\nActually, I already restarted after adding the allowFrom config and it didn't help. Let me check the config state more carefully - the tts account now has allowFrom and dmPolicy settings, which is different from before when it was inheriting from the global config. But wait, the old log showed \"feishu[tts]: sender ou_42b0f5aa... not in DM allowlist\" even though the global allowFrom contained ou_f590c429. That's strange - if tts was inheriting from global, why would ou_42b0f5aa be rejected?\n\nLooking back at the startup logs, both feishu[kiit] and feishu[tts] started with websocket mode. But I don't see tts starting in the recent restart logs, which is suspicious. Maybe the tts account isn't actually being loaded after the restart, or it's failing to initialize properly. Let me look more carefully at what happened during that restart.\n\nActually, the real issue might be different. The user showed me a screenshot where TK Bot (cli_a930f78f51399bc6) is bound to \"main — KITT-AGI\" instead of \"tts — TK 选品大师\". So I unbound it and added tts account and binding back. But when the user tested, it still didn't work. Maybe the problem isn't the binding itself—perhaps the TK Bot in Feishu isn't properly configured with the right event subscriptions or permissions to receive messages in the first place.\n\nLet me trace through the message flow again. The user sends a DM to TK's app ID, Feishu receives it and routes it to the connected WebSocket for that app. OpenClaw should get it since it's maintaining that connection, then look up the app ID to match the correct account, check if the sender is allowed, create a session for the tts agent, and process the message. But the logs show kiit receiving the message instead of tts, which suggests something is intercepting or redirecting the message before it reaches the tts account. Since the config now has allowFrom and dmPolicy set to allowlist for tts, and the user isn't on ou_42b0f5aa's allowlist, that older user's messages should be blocked—but the user's messages should work if the routing was correct.\n\nThe user says they tested and only TK isn't responding while other bots work fine. This tells me the issue isn't about allowFrom or dmPolicy settings, because if those were wrong, no bot would respond. Instead, TK specifically isn't getting messages while others do. So the problem is at the routing layer—messages to TK's app ID are somehow being received by kiit's account instead of being routed to TK's account.\n\nThis could mean TK's WebSocket connection to Feishu is broken or never established in the first place. When the Gateway restarts, the startup logs show both kiit and tts accounts attempting to start, but there's no confirmation that tts's connection actually succeeded. If TK's WebSocket failed to connect while kiit's succeeded, then any message sent to TK would arrive at kiit instead, which would explain why only TK isn't responding.\n\nI should check the Gateway logs around the recent restart to see if tts actually connected or if it failed silently. Also, the user mentioned the TK app works through the web UI, which confirms the tts agent itself is running—but that doesn't mean its Feishu connection is active. Let me look more carefully at what the recent restart logs show to understand if tts managed to establish its WebSocket connection to Feishu.\n\nWait, I just realized something from the message logs. When the user's message came through at 21:36:53, it was received by feishu[kiit] from ou_f590c429. But there's no corresponding feishu[tts] log entry for the same message ID. That gap is telling—if tts had received the message, I'd see that log entry right after the kiit one. The absence means tts didn't process it.\n\nBut what if the same message is being delivered to both accounts through different connections? That would be unusual for Feishu, since a message to one bot's appId shouldn't go to another bot's appId. Unless there's something wrong with how the message is being routed internally.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. The user is testing the TK bot in Feishu, and it's not responding. The session for ou_f590c429 doesn't exist under tts, only under kiit. So the message is reaching kiit instead of tts. The user says they're sending to TK, so they must be using TK's appId. Why would the Gateway route it to kiit?\n\nUnless the issue is at the Feishu level—if the user doesn't have TK's app installed or there's some mismatch between what the user thinks they're sending and what's actually being delivered. But the user confirmed they're sending to TK, so that doesn't make sense either.\n\nLet me check if there's a way to test TK's connection directly, or maybe just try recreating the TK account from scratch to see if that fixes the routing issue. Actually, I'm wondering if there's a conflict at the routing layer. Let me look at the defaultAccount setting and how it interacts with the routing configuration. The bindings array is ordered with main routing to kiit first, then tts, and so on. But the kiit account might be handling some kind of catch-all behavior that's intercepting TK's messages before they reach the tts handler.\n\nLet me try removing the kiit account entirely and restart to see if that changes the behavior. But first, I need to check if there's something specific about how messages are being routed that I'm missing.\n\nActually, looking at the account configurations more carefully - tts has `connectionMode: \"websocket\"` set explicitly, while other accounts just inherit the global setting. That's the only real difference between them. Let me check if removing that explicit override helps, or if there's something else going on with how the connection mode is being applied.\n\nWait - I'm noticing something important in the chat_id metadata. The sender_id and conversation info both show `user:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb`, which suggests this message is coming from the current session context. But the earlier logs showed a different open_id being blocked. The current user should have access, so the allowlist shouldn't be preventing anything. Maybe the issue isn't the allowlist at all - perhaps the message routing itself is going to the wrong account, or there's something about how the session context is being used that's causing the conflict.\n\nLooking at the feishu log entries, kiit successfully received the message and created a session, but tts never saw it. This means the Gateway is routing to kiit instead of tts for some reason. The question is why - if both accounts have allowFrom configured and the sender is in kiit's allowlist, the Gateway should be routing correctly. Unless the Gateway isn't properly recognizing tts as a separate account, or there's an issue with how the routing is being resolved.\n\nI should try restarting the Gateway to see if that forces a proper reload of the account configurations.\n","thinkingSignature":"e0b16809dc53e8d445cc133bfb6377cef857cf4bd29beeb50d08b66eac7eb871"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0u5cdn2in35v_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 500 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep -E \"starting feishu|feishu\\[.*\\]:.*start|WebSocket.*start\" | tail -30","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":103,"output":3330,"cacheRead":108756,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112189,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779543643168,"responseId":"0660e15b414f18e1edbc5c58bdca6171"}}
