{"type":"message","id":"70e0bcca","parentId":"09b825b0","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:44:38.715Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the clear picture:\n\n1. At 21:36:21, `feishu[tts]` received a message from `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` - this is NOT the current user (ou_f590c429), this is an OLD user. And it says \"not in DM allowlist\". So TK is receiving messages, but from the OLD user (ou_42b0f5aa) which is not in the allowlist.\n\n2. At 21:36:53, `feishu[kiit]` received a message from `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` - this IS the current user. And it dispatched to agent:main (kiit).\n\nSo the problem is: when the USER (ou_f590c429) sends a message to TK, it goes to kiit, NOT to tts.\n\nWhy? Because when the user opens TK's chat in Feishu, they are actually opening kiit's DM!\n\nLet me think about this. The user opens the TK bot in Feishu. The TK bot has appId `cli_a930f78f51399bc6`. Feishu delivers the message to the app with that appId. But somehow the message is going to kiit?\n\nWait - let me check the chat IDs:\n- The old user (ou_42b0f5aa) sent to `oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8` - this is TK's chat (tts)\n- The current user (ou_f590c429) sent to `oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8` - this is kiit's chat\n\nSo the user (ou_f590c429) is sending to kiit's chat (oc_891331...), not TK's chat! That's why it's going to kiit - the user opened kiit's DM, not TK's DM!\n \nBut the user said they opened TK's bot. So why is the chat_id oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8 mapped to kiit?\n\nActually wait - the metadata shows this message's chat_id is `oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8`. This is the SAME chat_id that appears in the kiit log at 21:36:53. So yes, the user is sending to kiit's DM.\n\nBut why? The user said they opened TK's bot. And the appId is cli_a930f78f51399bc6 which is TK's appId. How is it going to kiit?\n\nUnless... when the user opens TK's bot in Feishu, if they previously had a DM with kiit, Feishu might be routing them to the existing DM instead of creating a new one for TK. But the appId should determine routing, not the chat history. Let me look at the gateway restart log to see if there's a clue about why this is happening.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be that when the user deleted the binding and re-added it, something went wrong with how the TK bot's appId is being resolved. The user unlinked the binding and re-added the account, but the config shows `cli_a930f78f51399bc6` is correctly bound to the tts account. So the message routing should work - unless there's something else going on with how the account is being resolved at runtime.\n\nWait, I'm seeing something at 21:12 - the feishu[tts] received a message at that timestamp. Let me check what happened right before that to see if there's a pattern.\n\nActually, the real question is: does the user want the TK bot to receive messages from both user IDs or just one? Currently the TK bot only allows ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb. If they want ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 to also receive messages, that would need to be added to the allowFrom list. But the user's complaint was that messages aren't getting through at all.\n\nWait - I think I found it. When the user \"解除绑定\" (unlinked) the TK bot in that third-party management panel, they removed the binding between the TK app and the tts account. After that, when the user sends messages to the TK app, Feishu is routing them to kiit instead of tts - because the routing is broken. My fix just re-added the config but didn't restore the binding in the third-party panel itself.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The user said the app_id is correct (cli_a930f78f51399bc6), so it's going to the right app. But the binding might not be the issue - maybe the problem is simpler. I should check if the user is actually opening a DM with the TK bot or if something else is going on with how the messages are being routed.\n\nLet me think about this differently. When the user sends a message to TK, Feishu delivers it to app cli_a930f78f51399bc6. The gateway receives it and looks up the account by appId. It finds tts in the accounts list, then checks the binding for accountId=tts and channel=feishu. The binding should point to agentId=tts. But something in this chain isn't working - maybe the message is being delivered but never creating a session, or the dispatch isn't happening at all.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider the user's original complaint. They said \"TK选品大师没有回复\" but didn't clarify which bot they're messaging. Looking at the metadata I have, the message came from ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb at 21:36:53 - this is the user's message to kiit, not to TK. The actual message_id for TK would be om_x100b6e2e9b89aca8c32dac353a00451 from the same timestamp, but I'm not seeing a response to that one. So the issue is: the user sent a message to TK (om_x100b6e2e9b89aca8c32dac353a00451) but there's no reply, while kiit (om_x100b6e2e998b3938c2539f6735a6d4b) did get a response.\n\nActually, I think I see what's happening. When the user opens the TK bot in Feishu, they're getting the kiit chat instead. The user unlinked the binding in the management panel, which might have caused TK to default to kiit's configuration. Even though I re-added the config, if the panel has TK bound to main, that's where messages will route. The user might be testing TK but inadvertently messaging kiit because the binding got mixed up.\n\nLet me step back though - there are other agents like content and finance that work fine, so the user is probably testing those too and noticing TK specifically doesn't respond. The user confirms TK is the only one broken. This suggests the problem isn't a general routing issue - it's specific to how TK's feishu bot is configured or bound.\n\nLooking at the logs, when messages come through feishu[tts] they get rejected for the wrong sender, but feishu[kiit] works fine. This tells me the feishu plugins are running for both, but the allowFrom configuration for TK is blocking the user while kiit isn't. The user says they unlinked TK in the management panel, so maybe that's caused the app to fall back to some default configuration where it's using kiit's credentials or routing instead of its own.\n\nI think what's actually happening is the user unlinked the TK bot account in that third-party management panel, which dropped the accountId from the configuration. When they re-added it, the account was recreated but the accountId field stayed empty. That would explain why messages to TK are being processed by the kiit plugin instead - the accountId isn't set on the TK bot, so it has no way to distinguish itself.\n\nThough the config shows accountId as \"tts\" for the TK bot, so that should be fine. Let me just tell the user to test it and see if the next message to TK actually gets through.\n\nWait, I should check what's happening right now with the current gateway process - maybe it's running an older version of the config before my changes took effect.\n","thinkingSignature":"df402f2be9aaa2b537356c8a0e53daa3f9d082d6d0d8e20c4dbc9e0aa3b32277"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3ornnntb9qks_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep \"openclaw\" | grep -v grep | head -5","timeout":5}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3ornnntb9qks_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /home/halei/.openclaw/agents/tts/sessions/*.jsonl 2>/dev/null | tail -5","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1115,"output":1901,"cacheRead":111868,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":114884,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779543833887,"responseId":"0660e21ad09127b24fd00104a87516bf"}}
