{"type":"message","id":"e84459f8","parentId":"cc1127d2","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:46:21.903Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The last feishu[tts] log was at 21:36. There are no new logs about feishu[tts] starting or receiving messages from ou_f590c429. This is very strange.\n\nActually, wait. Let me check the timestamp more carefully. Current time is roughly 21:43 (from the journalctl timestamps). The last tts log was at 21:36. But there was no log for tts receiving messages from ou_f590c429 at 21:36. \n\nActually the log shows:\n- 21:36:21 - feishu[tts] receives message from ou_42b0f5aa (old user, not ou_f590c429)\n- 21:36:53 - feishu[kiit] receives message from ou_f590c429\n\nSo at 21:36, when the user sent a message, it went to kiit, NOT to tts. Why?\n\nLooking at the feishu log: at 21:36:21, feishu[tts] received a message (but from ou_42b0f5aa, not ou_f590c429). This means the TK bot DID receive a message at that time. But then at 21:36:53, feishu[kiit] received a message from ou_f590c429. These are two DIFFERENT messages at two DIFFERENT times (21:36:21 and 21:36:53).\n\nWait - the user said \"不行\" (it doesn't work). They sent a message and TK didn't reply. But what we see in the logs is:\n- At 21:36:21, TK received a message from ou_42b0f5aa (not from ou_f590c429)\n- At 21:36:53, kiit received a message from ou_f590c429\n\nSo the user's message at ~21:36 went to kiit, NOT to TK. \n\nThis means the user's message is being routed to kiit. Either the user messaged kiit's bot (appId: cli_a93650c6fc785bce), or there's a routing issue where the message should go to tts but goes to kiit instead. The user's open_id is ou_f590c429, and looking at the sessions.json, there's no tts session for this user. But the user claims they messaged TK and it didn't reply. I think the user sent the message to kiit, not TK. Or more precisely - when the user opens the TK bot window in Feishu and sends a message, Feishu delivers it to the TK app (cli_a930f78f51399bc6), which OpenClaw receives via its feishu[tts] WebSocket. But the routing table shows the message was delivered to feishu[kiit] instead.\n\nActually, I see it now - the logs show feishu[tts] received a message at 21:36:21 from ou_42b0f5aa, not ou_f590c429. So the TK bot did receive a message, just not from the user's open_id. This means the user might have been messaging from a different account. But at 21:36:53, feishu[kiit] received a message from ou_f590c429, which is the user. So there are two separate messages here - one to TK from a different user, and one to kiit from the user.\n\nThe user confirmed \"不行\" (it doesn't work). They tested in Feishu and TK didn't respond, but other bots work fine. This suggests the message never reached TK's agent handler, or TK's WebSocket connection to Feishu is broken. Since the user's message went to kiit instead of TK, I need to figure out why the routing is going to kiit when it should go to TK. Let me check if the app ID for TK is being matched correctly when the message arrives.\n\nActually, I should reconsider - the user said they tested TK specifically in Feishu and it didn't work. They also mentioned the management panel shows TK bound to \"main\". But we know the bindings are correct in the config, so the issue might be elsewhere. Let me look at the account configuration more carefully to see if something's missing or misconfigured.\n\nLooking at the tts account, I see it has `connectionMode: \"websocket\"` explicitly set, which might be overriding the default behavior. Other accounts inherit from global, but tts doesn't. The allowFrom and dmPolicy are set correctly for tts, but the global settings should apply since tts inherits from global anyway. Maybe the WebSocket mode is causing the connection to behave differently than expected.\n\nBut actually, I'm wondering if the binding itself is the issue - the management panel is showing \"main — KITT-AGI\" as the binding for TK, not \"tts — TK 选品大师\". Even though the bindings in openclaw.json look correct, maybe the management panel is reading from a different source or there's a stale config somewhere.\n\nWait - I need to clarify what the user is actually asking me to do. They're asking me to do an internal test and send a message to TK to verify it's working, but they want me to use an internal method rather than going through Feishu directly. I can use the feishu_im_user_message tool to send a DM to TK's open_id, but that requires knowing TK's open_id first. Let me retrieve that from the gateway logs and send the test message through the API.\n\nActually, the real issue here is that the user is confused about how the routing works. When they send a DM to the TK bot in Feishu, it should be routed to the feishu[tts] account, not to kiit. But the logs show that when they send messages to TK, the logs are routing to feishu[kiit] instead. So either the message isn't actually going to TK's app_id, or there's something wrong with how the routing is configured between the app_id and the feishu account binding.\n\nThe user mentioned they tested in Feishu and TK didn't respond, but other bots did. This suggests the problem is specifically with TK's WebSocket connection to Feishu - either the app_id binding is incorrect or the connection itself is broken. I should verify that TK's bot configuration in Feishu is correct and that the app_id maps properly to the tts account.\n\nLet me try sending a test message directly to TK through the Feishu API to see if the bot can receive and respond to messages at all.\n","thinkingSignature":"128b449c815207c1b5c790cc2c191d2db5c76c92638e8e21ea8d9e4eab6ce05d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_6ge3vke90g01_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 5000 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep \"bot open_id resolved\" | tail -10","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":96,"output":1434,"cacheRead":113502,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":115032,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779543946375,"responseId":"0660e28b7aee32d44111b481464dcc27"}}
