{"type":"message","id":"c2020f5f","parentId":"3e931606","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:49:12.080Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The config looks correct. tts has allowFrom with the user's open_id.\n\nBut the journalctl shows that when the user (ou_f590c429) sends a message, it goes to kiit not tts. And tts is receiving messages from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 which is rejected.\n\nThis means the user's message to TK bot is actually being routed to kiit, not tts. Why?\n\nWait - the user said \"不行\" at 21:36. Looking at the logs:\n- 21:36:21 - feishu[tts] received message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 (rejected - not in allowlist)\n\n\n- 21:36:53 - feishu[kiit] received message from ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb\n\nSo the user sent \"不行\" to kiit at 21:36, but they said they tested TK and it didn't work. So they're saying TK didn't respond when they messaged it, not that kiit didn't respond. The user says TK still has no reply, other bots are fine - so when they messaged TK, it went to kiit instead.\n\nBut there's another possibility: maybe when the user is in the TK bot chat in Feishu and sends a message, the message is actually being sent to kiit because the user is chatting with the kiit bot rather than the TK bot directly. Though they did confirm the app_id is cli_a930f78f51399bc6 which is TK's. Yet the journalctl at 21:36:21 shows TK received a message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 (rejected), not from ou_f590c429 - so the user's message never even reached TK.\n\nThe user's message (ou_f590c429) went to kiit instead. This is very strange. There could be a session issue where the user previously had a session with kiit and when they open the TK bot chat in Feishu, it's resuming the kiit session rather than starting a new one with TK. Or when they send a message, it's being routed based on some session binding to kiit. The routing uses the accountId from the Feishu app (cli_a930f78f51399bc6) matched to the account name (tts), then dispatches to the agentId from the binding (tts). So the routing itself seems correct, but the message is still ending up at kiit. Let me check if there's something about the chat ID or message ID that explains why this particular message from the user went to kiit instead of TK.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully - at 21:36:53 the user (ou_f590c429) sent a message to kiit (chat oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8), which is this conversation with KIIT right now. That's normal. The user earlier said \"不行\" meaning TK doesn't work - they tried messaging TK but got no reply. The question is: what did the user actually send to TK? Did they send a message to TK at 21:36 that wasn't captured in the logs, or did they send \"不行\" to kiit because TK didn't respond?\n\nI should check if there's a log entry showing TK receiving a message from ou_f590c429 at around 21:35-21:36. Looking at 21:36:21, TK received a message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 instead - not the user. So either the user sent a message to TK that never reached OpenClaw, or they sent it somewhere else entirely. I'm wondering if the issue is that when the user opens the TK bot in Feishu and sends a message, Feishu might be routing it to kiit instead of TK. But that doesn't make sense - the app_id should determine routing. Unless the user is actually in a chat with kiit, not TK, and just thinks they're messaging TK. Let me check the message details more carefully. At 21:36:53, feishu[kiit] received a message from ou_f590c429, and the message_id is om_x100b6e2e998b3938c2539f6735a6d4b, which matches what I'd expect for the \"不行\" message being sent to kiit.\n\nLooking at the conversation metadata, the sender_id is ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb, and this current message with \"不行\" is coming from the WeChat channel (openclaw-weixin) with chat_id o9cq8083vqOtBnqSVgYMRV19aHTE. That's different from the Feishu chat where kiit is receiving messages. So the \"不行\" message is being sent from WeChat to kiit, not from Feishu to TK.\n\nBut when the user said \"不行\" after \"通信测试\", they were referring to testing the Feishu TK bot, not WeChat. So I'm confused about the actual context here - the user tested TK in Feishu and it didn't work, but the message I'm seeing is from WeChat. I think the issue might be with how the message was delivered. The user said they tested Feishu and TK didn't respond, but the message_id in the conversation metadata shows it came through WeChat. If they're testing TK in Feishu and not getting a response, yet I'm seeing their \"不行\" message here from WeChat, maybe the message didn't actually go to TK at all.\n\nLooking at the Feishu logs more carefully - at 21:36:21 feishu[tts] received a message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 and rejected it due to allowlist. But at 21:36:53 feishu[kiit] received a message from ou_f590c429. The TK bot (ou_09c92e096986a0fcd5b389561a0a1a84) never shows a message from ou_f590c429 reaching it. The user's message went to kiit instead of TK, which suggests a routing issue - the user's session might be stuck with kiit rather than properly connecting to TK through Feishu. the routing should be correct. But something isn't working.\n\nWait - I think I need to step back and think about this differently. The config and bindings look right, but the user's message to TK is going to kiit. \n\nMaybe there's a bug in how the routing works? Or maybe the binding for tts isn't being picked up properly?\n\nActually, let me check if there's a \"defaultAccount\" issue. The global config has `defaultAccount: \"kiit\"`. Could this mean that when a message doesn't match any binding, it defaults to kiit? But the message should match the tts binding since it's going to appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6 which maps to tts account...\n\nUnless the message is being handled before the routing is evaluated. Or maybe the binding for tts is somehow not working.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. What if I check the actual WebSocket connections for tts and kiit to see if there's a difference? Actually, I should check if the tts account's WebSocket is connected at all. Looking at the logs, I can see bot open_id messages for tts at 21:24:40 during startup, so it was connected. But there are no logs of tts receiving messages from ou_f590c429 - only from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68. Meanwhile kiit received a message from ou_f590c429 at 21:36:53, which is this conversation right now. So the user IS messaging kiit, not TK.\n\nThe issue is clear now: when the user opens the TK bot chat window and sends a message, it goes to kiit instead of TK. This could mean either the user is accidentally messaging kiit while thinking they're messaging TK, or the TK bot is misconfigured in Feishu so messages are being routed to the wrong app. I should ask the user to open the TK bot chat directly and verify it's actually TK they're messaging - maybe check the bot name in the chat window header or try a /help command to see which bot responds.\n\nActually, wait. I think the Feishu routing might be the real problem here. If the user opens TK's chat window, Feishu should deliver the message to TK's app using the correct app_id. But if TK's app isn't properly configured as a bot in Feishu, or its event subscription isn't set up correctly, the message might be getting lost or misdelivered. Let me suggest they send a direct test message to TK using its specific app_id link to verify it's working.\n\nBut actually, the user confirmed earlier that the app_id is cli_a930f78f51399bc6 and it is indeed TK's bot. So Feishu routing should be fine. Let me reconsider...\n\nThe user's message went to kiit, not TK. This means the message sent to TK's app_id is being delivered to kiit instead. This could only happen if:\n1. There's a bug in OpenClaw's routing\n2. The tk app_id (cli_a930f78f51399bc6) is somehow mapped to kiit account in OpenClaw's config\n\nBut the config show