sent a message, but Feishu is delivering it to kiit because there's some kind of session mapping issue.\n\nOr maybe - and this is just a wild guess - the issue is that the user is testing from WeChat, not Feishu, and the user said \"不行\" referring to testing TK in Feishu. But the message came through WeChat, not Feishu.\n\nThe metadata shows the current message is from WeChat. The user said \"不行\" (no good/not working). This could mean either the WeChat bot isn't working or they're referring to TK not working in Feishu.\n\nLet me just try to figure this out by asking the user for clarification.\n\nActually, the user said \"不行了\" which means \"it's not working\" - referring to TK not responding in Feishu. The message came through WeChat to kiit (me). So the user is telling me from WeChat that TK in Feishu isn't working.\n\nBut the user also said \"你可以内部测试一下，发消息给他\" (you can test internally, send a message to him) - meaning I (KIIT) should send a test message to TK internally to see if TK responds. But I can't send agent-to-agent messages because it's disabled. I could try via the tts session's webchat but that's not the same as sending a Feishu DM to TK.\n\nOK let me try a different approach. Let me manually trigger a test by using the sessions_send to see if tts responds. But that was disabled earlier.\n\nWait - let me think about what else I can try. The user's issue is that when they send a message to TK in Feishu, TK doesn't respond. And I've confirmed that the tts account config is correct (appId, allowFrom, dmPolicy). The binding for tts is also correct.\n\nSo why isn't it working?\n\nLet me check if there's a bug in how OpenClaw is routing the message. When a message comes in from Feishu with appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6, OpenClaw looks up the account by appId. It should find the tts account. Then it checks the binding for accountId=tts and channel=feishu. It should find agentId=tts.\n\nBut the message is going to kiit instead. So either the account lookup is wr