{"type":"message","id":"c0633fca","parentId":"2f4539c9","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:51:01.806Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! Looking at all the accounts, the tts account has the most restrictive settings:\n- allowFrom: only ou_f590c429 (the user)\n- dmPolicy: allowlist (only allowlisted users can DM)\n\nAll other accounts have:\n- allowFrom: None (inherit from global allowFrom which includes ou_f590c429)\n- dmPolicy: None (inherit from global dmPolicy which is allowlist)\n\nSo tts is actually the MOST restrictive, not less restrictive. That makes sense with the \"allowlist\" policy.\n\nBut wait - looking at the global settings earlier, the global allowFrom is `['ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb']` and global dmPolicy is `allowlist`. \n\nSince kiit and other accounts inherit these global settings, the question is whether they're actually working as expected. The fact that kiit receives messages from the user but tts doesn't suggests the issue isn't with the configuration itself, but rather with message routing. Either messages aren't being sent to tts's websocket connection, or tts's allowlist is rejecting them despite the configuration looking correct. Let me verify if the bindings are actually being applied by the routing logic.","thinkingSignature":"85e7b38eee523865d36f19d0567b97cae852627a847effdff120f382bbc4df9b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_f6ahn967homp_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\nwith open('/home/halei/.openclaw/openclaw.json') as f:\n    cfg = json.load(f)\n\n# 检查 agentRoutes / routing 完整结构\nprint('Top-level keys with routing/binding:')\nfor key in cfg:\n    if 'route' in key.lower() or 'bind' in key.lower():\n        print(f'  {key}:', json.dumps(cfg[key], indent=2)[:500])\n\nprint()\n# 检查 agents 列表\nprint('Agents:')\nfor agent in cfg.get('agents', []):\n    print(f'  id={agent.get(\\\"id\\\")} name={agent.get(\\\"name\\\")}')\n\"","timeout":5}}],"api