{"type":"message","id":"543b28cb","parentId":"396b9c9e","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:51:44.267Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is very revealing! Looking at the journalctl logs for feishu[tts]:\n\nThe tts WebSocket keeps getting disconnected and restarted repeatedly:\n- 21:11:24 - started\n- 21:11:26 - stopped (only 2 seconds later!)\n- 21:11:47 - started\n- 21:11:51 - stopped (only 4 seconds later!)\n- 21:12:09 - started\n\nThis is a restart loop! The tts connection keeps dying and restarting. This explains why messages aren't getting through - the WebSocket connection is unstable.\n\nNow looking at the account configuration, the tts account has `allowFrom` and `dmPolicy` set correctly. \n\nBut I'm noticing something odd - the defaultAccount is set to \"kiit\", but the global allowFrom already includes the user's open ID, and the global dmPolicy is set to allowlist. So the user's message should be reaching the tts account, yet it keeps getting routed to kiit instead. The issue isn't with the message policy itself - it's that despite having the binding route configured to route messages to tts, something in the routing logic is sending them to kiit's session instead.\n\nThe tts WebSocket is crashing repeatedly, which would prevent it from processing any messages at all. Even though the message is being delivered to the correct session (agent:main:feishu:default:direct:ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb), that session is attached to kiit, not tts. But here's the thing - the user confirmed they're messaging the TK bot with app_id `cli_a930f78f51399bc6` (which is the tts account), yet the feishu logs show the message going to kiit instead. So either the message is being sent to the wrong bot, or there's a mismatch between what the user thinks they're messaging and what's actually receiving it.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that TK's WebSocket connection is dropping every few seconds, so when the user sends a message, the connection is temporarily dead and the message either queues or gets misrouted. I need to check the gateway logs after the 21:12 restart to see if the WebSocket connection stabilized or kept failing, and whether the user's messages after 21:36 are reaching the right place. Looking at the flow: the user's message comes in with metadata showing sender `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb`, and the routing logic appears to be matching based on sender ID rather than the intended target. d to feishu[default] for delivery\n4. feishu[default] has `dmPolicy=pairing` and `allowFrom=null` (inherits global), global `allowFrom=['ou_f590c429']`\n5. So the message goes through to main/kiit session\n\nThe issue is the user is sending to the TK bot (tts account, appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6), but the Feishu API delivers messages from the SAME open_id regardless of which bot's conversation window the user clicks. All bots share the same event push URL. So the router needs to figure out which account (and hence which agent) should handle the message.\n\nThe router uses the bindings, and the tts binding should match. But maybe the message isn't even reaching the router because the tts WebSocket is in a restart loop and Feishu might be buffering or dropping messages.\n\nThe real problem is that when a user clicks on the TK bot in Feishu and sends a message, that message should go through the tts account if the routing is configured correctly. But the fact that messages are going to feishu[kiit] instead suggests the routing logic isn't working as expected. I need to check how the router actually matches incoming messages to bindings - it should be using the message's metadata to determine which account it came from, but something in that matching process is failing.\n\nLooking at the message metadata more carefully, the chat_id points to the user's open_id, not the bot's. In Feishu's P2P message format, each bot-user pair has a unique chat_id, so I can't determine the account just from the chat_id alone. The only way to route correctly is to look at the message_id's open_id or the sender_id to identify which bot received the message, but Feishu doesn't include the receiving bot's open_id in the event push. This is the fundamental issue - without knowing which bot received the message, the router can't determine which binding to use, so all messages from the same user appear identical regardless of which bot window they were sent from. is a separate bot account. So the routing decision must happen at the Feishu platform level - when a user sends a message to TK bot, Feishu routes it to that specific bot's WebSocket connection. The issue might be that my bindings aren't correctly specifying which accountId should receive messages for that bot, or the message is getting routed to kiit's session instead because the accountId matching is wrong. I need to look more carefully at what the logs show about where the message actually ended up. The issue is that tts isn't in the active session list at all, but kiit is. So when a message comes in through the tts binding, Feishu routes it to kiit's WebSocket instead—either because tts's connection keeps dropping or because the routing itself is broken. I need to figure out why tts's session isn't being established or maintained.\n\nThe user's metadata shows the message was sent to the tts account's chat, but it got delivered to kiit's session instead. Looking at the event data, the message_id and chat_id are different from what was previously logged for kiit, suggesting the routing logic might be picking the wrong account based on the sender_id. The tts account config looks correct with appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6 and a proper allowFrom filter, but something in the binding logic is routing it to kiit instead. kiit. This suggests the user might actually be sending to the kiit bot, not tts. Let me verify the chat IDs: if the user's chat with kiit is oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8 and their chat with tts is oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8, then the message at 21:12:11 going to oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 was correctly sent to tts. But I need to check if there are other messages going to oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 that might be getting routed to kiit instead.\n\nActually, I think I've found the real issue. The messages the user is sending aren't showing up in the logs at all, which means they're not being received. The tk bot's WebSocket is restarting every 2-4 seconds and never stabilizes, so it's not actually receiving the messages being sent to it.\n\nLet me trace through the log entries more carefully - there's one message at 21:12:11 going to the tk chat (which is why ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 is there), but then all subsequent messages are going to oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8 instead, which is the kiit chat. So either the user switched to messaging the kiit bot, or they're sending to both but the tk bot's connection is too unstable to receive anything consistently.\n\nI need to fix the tk WebSocket stability problem first, then clear out those old sessions so the user gets a fresh session when they message tk again. The tk WebSocket connection keeps restarting every few seconds, which means it's not actually staying connected to receive messages. I need to figure out why that loop is happening and stop it.","thinkingSignature":"991854c02bd6d14e54b081c3b5fc5e6af78b6e15a0a07f41a57784b9e6a6933f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_x3objfozsfzd_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 5000 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep \"feishu\\[tts\\]\" | grep -vE \"stopping|started|dedup|WebSocket\" | tail -20","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1625,"output":1749,"cacheRead":66944,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":70318,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779544288449,"responseId":"0660e3e0f15307