{"type":"message","id":"a2d65800","parentId":"03d41d54","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:51:56.028Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture:\n\n1. The user's messages are going to `kiit` account (feishu[kiit]), not to `tts` account (feishu[tts])\n2. The `tts` account IS receiving messages - but from a different user `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` (which is another user who is NOT in the allowlist)\n3. The tts WebSocket is active and connected - it just can only receive messages from the allowlisted user `ou_f590c429`\n\n\n4. The routing issue is that messages from `ou_f590c429` are being routed to the `kiit` account instead of `tts`, and I need to check the routing configuration to understand why the `tts` binding isn't being used for that user\n\n. The binding for `tts` is set up correctly with the matching `accountId: \"tts\"` and `channel: \"feishu\"`, so the issue must be in how the accountId is being determined for that sender.\n\nLet me trace through the journal logs more carefully - when the user sends a message, it appears at `feishu[tts]` which means it is reaching the right account, but then something about the message content or the session state is causing it to be rejected, even though the sender's open_id should be in the allowlist.\n\nLooking at the routing logic: if the message's sender_id (`ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb`) matches the account's allowFrom list and the accountId matches the tts binding, then it should route to the tts agent. But maybe there's a session affinity issue where an existing session is forcing the message to the kiit account instead, or the account resolution itself is failing before it even gets to the routing decision. The message from 21:36:21 came through the tts account successfully, but the user is saying it's not being delivered to the TK bot in Feishu. I need to trace whether tts actually has a Feishu session for this user and if the agent is even connected.\n\nLooking at the sessions data, there's only a webchat session for tts and an old Feishu session from another user, but nothing for `ou_f590c429`. So even though the message reached the tts account, there's no active session to handle it. The issue might be that the message is reaching tts but there's no session to process it, or the kiit account is handling everything while tts remains idle. Let me trace through what's happening to the user's message after it arrives at the tts WebSocket, since the kiit account seems to be processing normally but tts might be getting stuck somewhere in the flow. I'm checking the routing logs to see which account is actually receiving the user's message - the journal entries show kiit getting the message at 21:36:53, but the user's test was for TK, so I need to figure out where the tts account fits in and whether the session routing is working correctly. I need to trace where the user's message from TK is actually going. The journal shows `feishu[kiit]` handling it at 21:36:53, but there should be a corresponding entry for `feishu[tts]` since the user sent it to TK's app. Let me check the timing more carefully—if the user messaged TK around 21:36:21 based on the timestamp, I should look for whether that message appears in the tts logs or if it's being routed somewhere else entirely. the tts account isn't processing messages from `ou_f590c429` because there's no session for that user—it only shows logs for messages from `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68`. I need to figure out why the routing logic isn't dispatching to an agent when it should be.\n\nLet me trace through the message flow after it arrives at tts to see where the dispatch is failing. The kiit account is processing normally and dispatching to `agent:main:main`, so the kiit routing is working. The question is why tts isn't following the same pattern when a message comes in from the correct user.\n\nI should check if there's a rate limit, webhook issue with the TK app setup, or if the tts WebSocket is actually connected despite the logs showing it started. Let me try restarting the gateway and testing again to see if the tts account wakes up.\n\nActually, wait—the user is asking me to test internally, not just have them test from Feishu. I should send a message to the tts agent directly using sessions_send to verify it's actually receiving and processing messages.\n\nBut first, I need to clarify how to address the tts agent—whether it's agent ID \"tts\" or if there's a different naming convention. Let me check the current session structure to understand how the tts agent is set up.","thinkingSignature":"5d85194f110e64a9f58d349e3cdc825003200db412a736a512a8243068ef97c1"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n日志里发现一个关键线索——你的消息进的是 `kiit` 账号，不是 `tts` 账号。我先直接给 tts agent 发条测试消息试试：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_gby5e74ct0xm_1","name":"sessions_list","arguments":{"agentId":"tts","messageLimit":1}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1679,"output":1121,"cacheRead":68544,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71344,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779544304804,"responseId":"0660e3f15d1a609d255bb4c713f417de"}}
