{"type":"message","id":"d068df33","parentId":"f0b19b15","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:52:05.237Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! sessions_list with agentId=tts returns 0 sessions, but we know there are sessions in the sessions.json file. This suggests the sessions_list tool may be looking for currently active sessions with the tts agent that have recent activity, not historical sessions from the JSON file.\n\nThe tts agent has no active feishu session for ou_f590c429. Let me try to directly send a message to the tts agent via sessions_send to trigger it, or better yet, let me try to use the message tool to send to the tts feishu account directly.\n\nActually wait - let me re-read the problem. The user sends a message from their Feishu app to the TK bot. The TK bot (tts account) receives it via WebSocket. The feishu[tts] channel then needs to dispatch it to the tts agent. \n \nSo the dispatch should happen after the allowlist check passes, but ou_f590c429 isn't showing up in the recent tts session logs at all—even though we fixed the allowFrom setting to include that user. Yet kiit received the same message without issue. This is really strange.\n\nThe chat IDs are different though. ou_f590c429 appears in two separate conversations: one with the TK bot using chat_id oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8, and another with kiit using oc_891331ffe537b34aa96f0be8874885c8. It's possible ou_f590c429 is actually two different people, but that doesn't make sense since it's the same user ID.\n\nLooking at the timeline more carefully, when the user tried testing with \"通信测试\", it went to kiit instead. Then later when they sent another message, they were specifically testing in the TK bot window, which is why that message went to tts instead. That's the key difference—the routing depends on which bot window the user is interacting through.\n\nThe issue now is that when the user sends a message directly to TK (tts account), it's not creating a new session. The kiit agent is still processing the 21:37 message from the user, which might be blocking the tts agent from creating its own session.\n\nLooking at the configuration, the global settings show defaultAccount is \"kiit\" with allowFrom and dmPolicy both set to allowlist for the user. But the kiit account itself has no overrides for these settings, so it's inheriting the global defaults. This means kiit should be allowing the user, but there might be a conflict with how tts is configured that's preventing it from handling messages properly. Both accounts inherit the global allowlist, so that's not the issue. I'm wondering if the problem is that when a user sends a message to the TK bot via the app, Feishu creates a session—but since we've never created a session for ou_f590c429 on the tts account, the message might be getting handled differently than expected. Maybe the allowlist check itself is fine, but something about how the sessionless message is being processed is causing the routing to fail.\n\nLet me try creating a test session for the user on the tts account so messages will route correctly instead of going to kiit.","thinkingSignature":"9a2aa23eb1574b6c7602c5aea1b2e6e3a2264b614729ff9e0c25887e4f38a71d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5bgzyv47jlb2_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\nwith open('/home/halei/.openclaw/agents/tts/sessions/sessions.json') as f:\n    data = json.load(f)\n\n# Show ALL sessions\nfor k, v in data.items():\n    print(f'key: {k}')\n    print(f'  accountId in origin: {v.get(\\\"origin\\\",{}).get(\\\"accountId\\\")}')\n    print(f'  full origin: {json.dumps(v.get(\\\"origin\\\",{}))}')\n    print()\n\"","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":79,"output":810,"cacheRead":70208,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71097,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","times