{"type":"message","id":"b3910b29","parentId":"576f8777","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:53:06.060Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, but the binding `{type: \"route\", agentId: \"tts\", match: {channel: \"feishu\", senderId: \"ou_xxx\"}}` should route to the tts agent when the sender matches. But the senderId is the message sender's open_id - which would be the user's open_id when they message the TK bot. So this might work.\n\nBut wait - there's still the problem of the feishu[tts] channel receiving the message in the first place. The user messages the TK bot (appId cli_a930f78f51399bc6). The Feishu server routes to this bot's WebSocket. \n\nThe feishu[tts] channel receives it and checks allowFrom, but it's still rejecting the user with \"not in DM allowlist\" even though the config should have allowFrom set to their open_id. I think the issue is that tts account-level allowFrom isn't being inherited or merged with the global allowFrom - it might be replacing it entirely instead of combining the lists. The session lookup happens through feishu routing based on senderId, not through accountId matching, so the sender-based binding might actually route correctly even though the feishu[tts] channel doesn't exist in the session state.\n\nBut if allowFrom is set to allowlist and the sender's open_id is in the allowFrom list, it should work. Let me think through what messages the user sent to the TK bot in Feishu at 21:36-21:37 and whether the allowFrom check would pass for them.\n","thinkingSignature":"1a1aa93122e49827c97859e830381587c481d79b1e9413520af4251101ae5223"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_tq9rkqr7erud_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 5000 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep -E \"21:3[5-9]|21:4\" | grep -iE \"feishu\\[tts\\]\" | head -20","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":356,"output":410,"cacheRead":71520,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72286,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779544380262,"responseId":"0660e43c78b71d2a289c4837249cbcd8"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1d7dda3b","parentId":"b3910b29","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:53:06.351Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_tq9rkqr7erud_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"5月 23 21:36:21 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[523018]: 2026-05-23T21:36:21.023+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: message om_x100b6e2e9b89aca8c32dac353a00451 in chat oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 — immediate\n5月 23 21:36:21 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[523018]: 2026-05-23T21:36:21.535+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: received message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 in oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 (p2p)\n5月 23 21:36:21 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[523018]: 2026-05-23T21:36:21.539+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: sender ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 not in DM allowlist"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":117,"aggregated":"5月 23 21:36:21 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[523018]: 2026-05-23T21:36:21.023+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: message om_x100b6e2e9b89aca8c32dac353a00451 in chat oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 — immediate\n5月 23 21:36:21 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[523018]: 2026-05-23T21:36:21.535+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: received message from ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 in oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 (p2p)\n5月 23 21:36:21 halei-Surface-Pro-4 node[523018]: 2026-05-23T21:36:21.539+08:00 [feishu] feishu[tts]: sender ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68 not in DM allowlist","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779544386347}}
{"type":"message","id":"a1061d32","parentId":"1d7dda3b","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:53:12.375Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, my new binding is supposed to send messages from `ou_f590c429` to the `tts` agent. But it won't prevent `ou_42b0f5aa` messages from still going to the `tts` account.\n\nActually, there's another problem: the new binding has `senderId` but the feishu routing might not support `senderId` in the match. Let me check what fields the routing actually supports.\n\nBut I think the real issue is different. Let me reconsider:1. The tts feishu account receives messages for the TK bot (appId `cli_a930f78f51399bc6`)2. The binding routes by accountId=tts to agentId=tts3. \n\nWhen HALEI sends a message to the TK bot, the message should be routed to the tts agent, but instead it's going to the kiit agent. The problem is likely that when HALEI's message arrives at the TK bot, it's creating a new session instead of using an existing one. Since there's no existing tts feishu session for HALEI, the system might be falling back to the default agent. I need to check the OpenClaw documentation to understand how the routing mechanism actually works.","thinkingSignature":"13c0b3ec86294bb4ee2785909096ec15e18e7559cc0754505691beb2e452df0f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0ndnyg94yf68_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"senderId\" /home/halei/.npm-global/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/extensions/feishu/index.js 2>/dev/null | head -5","timeout":5}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0ndnyg94yf68_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"match.*field\\|routing.*match\\|dispatching.*agent\\|dispatch.*agent\" /home/halei/.npm-global/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/gateway.js 2>/dev/null | head -10","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":384,"output":408,"cacheRead":71872,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72664,"cost":{"input":0,"output"