{"type":"message","id":"66c4e38d","parentId":"eff4a1b4","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:53:22.151Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The senderId routing won't work. Let me revert and try a different approach. The core issue is that the defaultAccount=kiit, so when a message comes from HALEI's open_id, it goes to kiit.\n\nLet me revert the binding to accountId-based routing, and instead try to see if there's a way to set the default account differently or use a different routing mechanism.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. What if the problem is that kiit's session is ALREADY active (processing), and new messages from HALEI are just queuing behind it? What if I look at the kiit session and see if it's stuck?\n\nFrom the earlier logs:\n\n\nI can see there's a long-running session for kiit that's been processing for over 5 minutes and queued behind active work. This means when HALEI sends a message to the TK bot, it's being routed through the kiit account's existing session instead of creating a new one for the TK bot. But wait—HALEI sent directly to the TK bot, so why would that message route to kiit at all? The routing must be going through feishu[default] because of the defaultAccount setting. I should check if feishu[default] actually maps to kiit or if there's another account involved.\n\nLooking at the accounts structure, feishu[default] exists with a dmPolicy of pairing and no appId, so messages sent to a bot that don't have a specific route would fall back to this default account. But I don't see HALEI's messages ever appearing in the feishu[default] logs—their messages only show up under feishu[kiit], which suggests the routing is definitely going to kiit instead of to the TK bot's account.\n\nSo the routing logic for direct messages must be: messages to TK bot → tts account (because the binding matches accountId=tts) → but kiit is handling them instead. The issue might be how the message actually gets routed 