{"type":"message","id":"c591f744","parentId":"2247031b","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:53:35.455Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK let me think about this differently. The key problem is: why is `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` sending messages to `kiit` account instead of `tts` account?\n\nThe user sends from Feishu to TK bot (app_id `cli_a930f78f51399bc6`). Feishu delivers the message to OpenClaw. OpenClaw needs to route it to the `tts` account (which owns this app_id).\n\nBut instead it goes to `kiit`. Why?\n\nLooking at the logs:\n```\nfeishu[tts]: message om_x100b6e2e9b89aca8c32dac353a00451 in chat oc_7cf732f57be08738470059baa24bd6d8 — immediate\n\n\n```\n\nSo the `tts` account IS receiving the message from Feishu — it's just that the dispatcher can't find the sender in its allowlist and rejects it before it even gets routed anywhere.\n\nThe issue is clear: when `ou_f590c429` sends to TK bot, `feishu[tts]` receives the message and checks its `allowFrom` list, but my address isn't there. The dispatcher rejects it with the sender mismatch error, so it never gets to the routing logic that would match it to the tts agent.\n\nThe `not in DM allowlist` message proves the TTS account is processing my message, but it's blocking me as a sender rather than accepting and forwarding it to the agent.\n\n```\n\nI need to trace where this sender validation is happening in the code and check if there's a mismatch between what the allowFrom configuration expects versus what senderId the dispatcher is actually passing.","thinkingSignature":"cf87ca7e6e090770f83a87b97d7a088f1d4436c8d58f07ea98914865f6dea291"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cbhvn3gurncq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\nwith open('/home/halei/.openclaw/openclaw.json') as f:\n    cfg = json.load(f)\n\naccounts = cfg['channels']['feishu']['accounts']\ntts = accounts['tts']\nprint('tts account allowFrom:', tts.get('allowFrom'))\nprin