{"type":"message","id":"7d225c22","parentId":"1436cbc9","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:57:51.407Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see that tts is receiving messages from `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` and dispatching them to `agent:tts:main`. The allowlist check passed (because it went from \"not in allowlist\" to \"dispatching to agent\").\n\nThis means the dmPolicy=allowlist fix worked! The sender `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` is now accepted by the allowlist (because the global allowFrom includes `ou_f590c429`... wait no, `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` is NOT `ou_f590c429`).\n\n\nI'm confused about why `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` got rejected earlier but is now being allowed—it was definitely not in the allowFrom list before, yet now it's passing through and dispatching successfully.\n\nLooking at the timeline more carefully, the dmPolicy change from `pairing` to `allowlist` happened at 21:57, which aligns with when `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` started getting accepted, so that's likely the switch that resolved it. the allowlist now? Unless the pairing mode was also letting non-paired users through, and switching to allowlist somehow fixed it. But that doesn't make sense—pairing should be more permissive, not less.\n\nThe real difference between the two attempts is that the first had both `allowFrom=['ou_f590c429']` AND `dmPolicy=allowlist`, while the second attempt only had `dmPolicy=pairing`. Maybe the allowFrom list is what's actually blocking access, and the issue is that I'm not including the right sender ID there.\n\nBut then at 21:57:09, the user successfully switched to `dmPolicy=allowlist` and messages started flowing through with a different sender ID. So either the pairing mode was being restrictive in a way I'm not understanding, or there was something else changing between attempts.\n\nActually, looking at the timeline more carefully—21:56:29 shows the old pairing restriction still in effect, then 21:57:09 applies the new allowlist policy and messages get through. The difference is the policy change itself, not the sender. So allowlist mode is definitely working now.\n\nI should check if the current gateway process is still running the old configuration from before the restart, or if it's already picked up the new settings. The gateway is running but the feishu channel hasn't reloaded yet because of those deferred operations. Let me wait for it to fully reload and check if the user receives their reply. Though I'm also noticing something odd—the sender `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` is now passing the allowlist check, which doesn't make sense since that ID isn't in the allowed list either.\n\nWait, I think I see it now. The allowlist policy checks if the sender is in the allowFrom list, and in pairing mode it creates a pairing request when a non-paired sender tries to message. But when I switched to pairing mode earlier, the log showed that sender got rejected immediately without creating a pairing request. That suggests the issue isn't about paired vs unpaired users at all—something else is going on with how the policies are actually being enforced.\n\nLet me trace through what actually changed between 21:56:29 when the message was rejected and 21:57:09 when it was allowed. The dmPolicy changed from pairing to allowlist, so that's the only thing that could have caused the behavior shift. This is strange though—if allowlist was rejecting that sender before and pairing was also rejecting it, then switching to allowlist shouldn't suddenly allow it unless the sender was actually in the allowFrom list all along, or unless something else in the config changed that I'm not seeing.\n\nI'm wondering if the pairing request created at 21:56:29 actually got approved between the two timestamps, which would explain why the sender suddenly has access. But pairing is account-specific, so that doesn't quite make sense either. Let me focus on what I know is working: tts is dispatching messages to the agent. Now I need to figure out why the user isn't getting replies, especially since kiit wasn't responding either. Looking back at the kiit logs, I see a stalled session at 21:48:51 with the user's session stuck in processing, and another dispatch at 21:55:41 where kiit sent a typing reaction to the message. The session was processing but eventually completed at 21:55:37 with one reply, so kiit does send replies sometimes. The issue might be that the session gets stalled and stops responding to new messages.\n\nI should check what kiit's actual response was to understand if it's working properly. Let me also look at the kiit dispatch logs around 21:55 more carefully to see what messages were being exchanged and whether they got proper responses. I see the user is saying kiit isn't replying either, not just the TK bot. The kiit session shows \"replies=1\" at 21:55:37, but those replies might have gone elsewhere or failed to send. I should ask the user for clarification on what's actually not working, since both TK and kiit seem to have routing issues despite the dispatch logs showing replies were queued. The config looks correct with the allowlist and account bindings properly set, so I should let the gateway finish reloading and have the user test again to see if their message went through to TK. Meanwhile, I'm realizing the kiit issue might be that it's getting stuck in processing loops that never actually send replies, so I should investigate whether the reply count is misleading.\n\nLooking at the dispatch logs more carefully though—the replies are being counted before the agent even starts processing, which doesn't make sense if they're actual responses. I need to understand what those replies=1 and replies=2 counts actually represent, whether they're just acknowledgment messages or something else entirely. I should stop overthinking the dispatch semantics and just test it. Let me ask the user 