{"type":"message","id":"1426fbe5","parentId":"684b97f5","timestamp":"2026-05-23T13:58:28.098Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! Now `agent:tts:main` has `origin accountId: tts` (0.2 minutes ago). And the other user `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` has a tts session. So the tts feishu connection IS working for that other user!\n\nBut there's still no session for `ou_f590c429b7ded95568bebca2f534efdb` under tts. All messages from the main user go to kiit.\n\nThis is really strange. The routing is consistently sending the main user's messages to kiit instead of tts, even though the tts account is properly configured and receiving messages from another user.\n \nLet me think about this differently. The main user's messages are all going to kiit because that's set as the default account in OpenClaw's routing, and the main session is bound there. But when I check the bindings for other accounts like agent-orchestrator, they should route messages to their respective accounts if the routing is working correctly. So the question is why isn't tts getting its messages despite having a proper binding?\n\nI think the real issue might be that the user is testing from a different chat context than where these messages are being sent. If the user sends a message from the KIIT bot chat in Feishu rather than the TK bot chat, it would naturally route to kiit instead. And since the user reported \"TK bot has no reply\" but didn't specify which bot they're testing from, they might just be testing from kiit's chat by default. Or conversely, if they're sending from the TK bot but it has the wrong app credentials configured, that could also explain the routing confusion.\n\nLet me reconsider the actual problem: both bots are supposedly not replying, but only TK was reported as broken. Looking at the diagnostic data more carefully, the main session for kiit shows it was processing a tool call and actively running exec at that moment. I need to check what kiit was actually doing during that stalled period.\n\nThe key insight is that kiit's session is blocked on `queued_behind_active_work` — it's waiting for an active model call to finish before it can process new messages. The older 21:49 dispatch completed with one reply and then immediately received a new message, but that new message got queued because the previous model call was still running. So kiit isn't truly broken; it's just backlogged by its own active workload. The user probably sent a message after \"不行\" that kiit is still processing. Meanwhile, tk has been consistently failing with messages always routing to kiit instead.\n\nThe core problem is why tk messages route to kiit. I'm wondering if the tk app's event subscription is misconfigured — maybe it's subscribed to receive messages but those events are being forwarded to kiit's connection instead of tk's. But actually, each WebSocket connection is tied to a specific app, so that's not quite right.\n\nLet me think about this differently. When a user sends a message to a specific bot in Feishu, the Feishu server routes it based on which bot's app the user interacted with. The message should go to that specific app's WebSocket connection. But if tk's WebSocket connection is failing or not properly established, the Feishu server might fall back to some default routing behavior.\n\nI don't have enough visibility into Feishu's internal routing logic to know exactly what's happening here. Let me try a different approach and just wait for the system to reload and test both bots to see what actually breaks.\n\nWait, I just spotted something important in the logs. The sender `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` was NOT paired and got a pairing request created, whereas with allowlist mode it would just reject the message. So now with pairing mode, that sender is getting a pairing request instead of being blocked. That suggests the pairing mode change is actually working for that user. But the main user's messages still aren't showing up in the tts logs at all.\n\nThe dispatcher might be checking accountId routing before feishu's sender-based routing, which would explain why those messages never reach tts. Let me just ask the user to test both bots again now that the configuration has been updated.","thinkingSignature":"d2144e6f29668f1443f5aeb3fa04cb6f9429b5087f75a95ae44ba4251cb3ab0d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dba4ajehdwo0_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl -n 100 --no-pager 2>/dev/null | grep \"reload.*complete\\|restart\\|feishu\\[tts\\].*dispatch\" | tail -10","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":329,"output":959,"cacheRead":89696,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90984,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779544697328,"responseId":"0660e5795ce2855e4a49991ba6e18372"}}
